<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>The appellant (&ldquo;Veracity&rdquo;) undertook a tax plan to minimize provincial tax on the sale of its shares in ALL But for the tax plan, Veracity would have been liable for BC income tax on the entire capital gain realized on the sale.</P>
<P>The linchpin of the plan was a Quebec law that permitted Veracity to choose a taxation year for Quebec purposes that did not coincide with its taxation year for BC or federal tax purposes. Veracity established a taxable presence in Quebec and exercised that choice. In the result, only 10% of Veracity's capital gain was taxed in BC. The balance was not taxed in Quebec (or any other province).</P>
<P>BC, relying on the general anti-avoidance rule in the BC Act (the &ldquo;BC GAAR&rdquo;), reassessed Veracity on the basis that 100% of the capital gain was subject to BC income tax. The judge concluded that the reassessment was correct. That conclusion is wrong in law.</P>
<P>The judge's fundamental error was his assumption that Veracity's capital gain &ldquo;ought&rdquo; to have been provincially taxed &ldquo;somewhere&rdquo;. This incorrect assumption derailed the judge from conducting a disciplined analysis of the relevant provisions of the BC Act, as mandated by the Supreme Court of Canada.</P>
<P>Quebec deliberately adopted a tax regime that did not harmonize with federal law or the law of other provinces. Differences in provincial tax regimes inevitably and expectedly lead to some income not being provincially taxed. It is not the role of the BC GAAR to override a tax policy choice made by Quebec. The provincial GAAR decisions of other appellate courts have established that taking advantage of interprovincial differences is not abusive tax avoidance.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>1. The facts are set out in the judge's reasons and are not in dispute. Although Veracity does not agree with all of the judge's findings of fact, it does not allege that any of those findings should be reversed for palpable and overriding error.</P>
<P>2. In anticipation of the sale of ALI shares to McKesson, Mr. Peet proceeded with a tax plan known as the &ldquo;Quebec Year-End Shuffle&rdquo; (Q-YES).
<P1>Reasons, Appeal Record (&ldquo;AR&rdquo;), p. 33-34, &para;13&ndash;17</P1>
<P1>Partial Agreed Statement of Facts, Appeal Book (&ldquo;AB&rdquo;), Exhibit 2, &para;30</P1></P>
<P>3. Pursuant to the Q-YES plan, Mr. Peet and Pi Capital, Mr. Peet's holding company, undertook the following transactions with the following provincial income tax consequences (see also the timeline chart in the Appendix):
<P1>Reasons, AR, p. 34&ndash;36, &para;19</P1>
<P1>Partial Agreed Statement of Facts, AB, Exhibit 2, &para;32</P1>
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Incorporation of Veracity and choice of June 30 as its fiscal year end</UNDER></TI>
<P>(a) On June 10, 2002, Veracity was incorporated under the laws of BC. At all relevant times, Veracity was potentially liable for income tax under the BC Act because it had a &ldquo;permanent establishment&rdquo; in BC.
<P1>BC Act (<EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.B.C. 1996, c. 215), ss. 2(2), 14(2), the definition of &ldquo;permanent establishment&rdquo; in s. 1(1), and the definition of &ldquo;taxable income earned in the year in British Columbia&rdquo; in s. 13.3.</P1>
<P1>Federal Act (<EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp.), s. 124(4) and federal <EM>Income Tax Regulations</EM>, C.R.C. c. 478, Reg. 400(1)-(2) (definitions of &ldquo;taxable income earned in the year in a province&rdquo; and &ldquo;permanent establishment&rdquo;)</P1></P>
<P>(b) Veracity chose June 30 as the end of its corporate fiscal period, which automatically established its taxation year for federal/BC tax purposes. Its first federal/BC taxation year was June 10 to 30, 2002 and its second federal/BC taxation year was July 1, 2002 to June 30, 2003.
<P1>BC Act, definition of &ldquo;taxation year&rdquo; and &ldquo;fiscal period&rdquo; in s. 1(1)</P1>
<P1>Federal Act, s. 249(1), definition of &ldquo;taxation year&rdquo; and s. 249.1, definition of &ldquo;fiscal period&rdquo;</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Veracity acquired the ALI shares on a &ldquo;rollover&rdquo; basis</UNDER></TI>
<P>(c) In June, 2002, Mr. Peet and Pi Capital transferred their shares of ALI to Veracity.</P>
<P>(d) Veracity, Mr. Peet and Pi Capital made joint elections pursuant to s. 85 of the federal Act, with these tax consequences;
<P1>i) Mr. Peet and Pi Capital were deemed to receive proceeds of disposition for the transferred ALI shares in an amount equal to their tax cost, so that Mr. Peet and Pi Capital realized no capital gain on the disposition.</P1>
<P1>ii) Veracity's cost of the ALI shares was deemed to be the tax cost of those shares to Mr. Peet and Pi Capital, so that <UNDER>Veracity</UNDER> would realize the entire deferred capital gain on a future sale of the ALI shares.</P1>
<P1>iii) Mr. Peet and Pi Capital received shares of Veracity with a tax cost equal to their cost of the ALI shares.
<P2>Federal Act, s. 85(1)(a)</P2>
<P2>BC Act, definition of &ldquo;taxable income&rdquo; in s. 1(1)</P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Veracity sold the ALI shares</UNDER></TI>
<P>(e) in July, 2002, Veracity sold the ALI shares to 646543 BC and received cash proceeds.</P>
<P>(f) Veracity realized, in its federal/BC taxation year ended June 30, 2003, a capital gain on the sale of the ALI shares equal to the capital gain deferred by Mr. Peet and Pi Capital.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Veracity paid directors' fees in BC</UNDER></TI>
<P>(g) In July, 2002, Veracity paid $1,000 each to Mr. Peet and his spouse as directors' fees.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Veracity purchased units of Gaz Metro</UNDER></TI>
<P>(h) In July and September, 2002, Veracity purchased units of Gaz Metropolitan &amp; Company Limited Partnership (&ldquo;Gaz Metro&rdquo;).</P>
<P>(i) Gaz Metro was a publicly-traded limited partnership with an &ldquo;establishment&rdquo; in Quebec (analogous to a &ldquo;permanent establishment&rdquo; under the federal Act). Its fiscal year end was September 30.
<P1>Quebec Act (the <EM>Taxation Act</EM>, CQLR c I-3), s. 12&ndash;16.2</P1></P>
<P>(j) The purchase of Gaz Metro units resulted in Veracity having:
<P1>(1) an &ldquo;establishment&rdquo; under the Quebec Act, so that Veracity became potentially liable for Quebec income tax; and</P1>
<P1>(2) a &ldquo;permanent establishment&rdquo; in Quebec under the federal rules for the allocation of taxable income to a province.</P1></P>
<P>(k) The Gaz Metro units were a reasonable stand-alone investment, although Veracity bought them primarily to follow the Q-YES plan.
<P1>Reasons, AR, p. 38, &para;27</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Veracity selected an August 31 taxation year end for Quebec tax purposes</UNDER></TI>
<P>(l) Veracity selected August 31 as its taxation year end for Quebec income tax purposes.</P>
<P>(m) Veracity's first Quebec taxation year ran from June 14 to August 31, 2002.</P>
<P>(n) Veracity's sale of the ALI shares occurred in that Quebec taxation year.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Gaz Metro made its year-end allocations to unit-holders</UNDER></TI>
<P>(o) On September 30, 2002, Gaz Metro's fiscal year end, Gaz Metro allocated to Veracity its proportionate share of Gaz Metro's gross revenues, and Gaz Metro's salaries and wages.</P>
<P>(p) The Gaz Metro allocations as of September 30, 2002 fell within Veracity's federal/BC taxation year ended June 30, 2003, and its Quebec taxation year ended August 31, 2003.</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The rules for the allocation of taxable income to the provinces</UNDER></TI>
<P>4. Under the BC Act, the taxable income earned in BC of a corporation with a permanent establishment in BC is determined using the formula in the federal Act and regulations. The federal formula allocates the corporation's taxable income to all provinces in which the corporation has a permanent establishment. The income allocation formula in the Quebec Act and regulations allocates taxable income to Quebec in substantially the same way.
<P1>BC Act, ss. 2(2), 13.3, 14(2)</P1>
<P1>Federal Act, s. 124(4) and federal Reg. 400(1)</P1>
<P1>Quebec Act, s. 22, 27, 771, Reg 771R4</P1></P>
<P>5. The formulas allocate taxable income to a province based in equal part on (a) the proportion of gross revenues received in the province to total gross revenues, and (b) the proportion of salaries and wages paid in the province to total salaries and wages.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Veracity's Quebec and BC income as reported</UNDER></TI>
<P>6. In its Quebec income tax return for the Quebec taxation year ended <UNDER>August 31, 2002</UNDER>, and in its federal/BC income tax return for the federal/BC taxation year ended <UNDER>June 30, 2003</UNDER>, Veracity reported its taxable capital gain from the sale of its ALI shares.</P>
<P>7. In its Quebec taxation year ended August 31, 2002, Veracity had no taxable income allocated to Quebec. Under the provincial allocation formula as applied for that year, 100% of Veracity's salaries and wages paid (the director's fees) were attributable to BC, and it had no gross revenues from Gaz Metro or from any other source. (Capital gains are not revenue for this purpose).</P>
