<P>11. If Veracity had chosen June 30 as its taxation year end for the purposes of the Quebec Act, the provincial allocation formula would have caused 89.8% of the taxable capital gain on the ALI shares to be taxable in Quebec. <UNDER>The BC allocation would still have been 10.2%</UNDER>.</P>
<P>12. Veracity concedes the following:
<P1>(a) When Veracity entered into the Q-YES Plan transactions, it intended to rely on the Quebec Act difference from the BC Act (and federal Act) relating to the permitted choice of taxation year end, so that most of the capital gain on the sale of the ALI shares would not be taxed under the BC Act, and none of it would be taxed under the Quebec Act.</P1>
<P1>(b) The Q-YES Plan transactions comprise a series of transactions undertaken primarily to obtain a &ldquo;tax benefit&rdquo; as defined in the BC GAAR.</P1>
<P1>(c) The conditions in s. 68.1(1)(b) of the definition of &ldquo;avoidance transaction&rdquo; in the BC GAAR are met.</P1>
<P1>(d) The exception in s. 68.1(1)(c) does not apply.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The reassessment</UNDER></TI>
<P>13. On December 28, 2011, the Minister of National Revenue reassessed Veracity for the federal/BC taxation year ended June 30, 2003. The Minister applied the BC GAAR (s. 68.1 of the BC Act) to allocate 100% of Veracity's taxable income in that year to BC, increasing Veracity's BC income tax payable by $1,175,249.
<P1>Partial Agreed Statement of Facts, AB, Exhibit 2, &para;47</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The appeal</UNDER></TI>
<P>14. Veracity appealed the reassessment to the Supreme Court of British Columbia The judge dismissed the appeal. Veracity now appeals to this Court.
<P1>Notice of Appeal, AR, p. 1; Reasons, AR, p. 30</P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ERRORS IN JUDGMENT</TI>
<P>15. The judge erred in law when he failed to follow the statutory framework mandated by the Supreme Court of Canada in the GAAR jurisprudence, and in particular:
<P1>(a) he based his analysis on the false premise that the entire capital gain &ldquo;ought&rdquo; to have been subject to tax in a province, which i) derailed him from correctly applying the GAAR jurisprudence and ii) ignored the fact that there is no uniform system of provincial taxation;</P1>
<P1>(b) he concluded incorrectly that the BC GAAR could be applied to override an explicit tax policy choice made by Quebec;</P1>
<P1>(c) he failed to limit his analysis to statutory provisions that are within the scope of the BC GAAR; and</P1>
<P1>(d) he failed to determine correctly, or at all, the object, spirit and purpose of the provisions of the BC Act upon which Veracity relied to obtain the &ldquo;tax benefit&rdquo; (as defined in the BC GAAR).</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The standard of review is correctness</UNDER></TI>
<P>16. All of the issues under appeal are questions of law, reviewable on appeal on the standard of correctness. As the judge failed to analyze the relevant statutory provisions, and did not properly determine the object, spirit and purpose of the relevant statutory provisions, the judge's findings on &ldquo;misuse or abuse&rdquo; are not entitled to deference.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Canada Trustco Mortgage Co. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2005 SCC 54</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Landrus</SOC><CITE>2009 FCA 113</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Preliminary comment</UNDER></TI>
<P>17. The judge's observation that Veracity &ldquo;adopted contradictory positions&rdquo; about its taxable income allocation for purposes of the BC Act and the Quebec Act discloses a fundamental misapprehension of the applicable statutory schemes.
<P1>Reasons, AR, p. 48, &para;56</P1></P>
<P>18. What the judge characterized as a contradiction was the result of the differences between the taxation laws of BC and Quebec as to the permitted choice of taxation year ends. There was no inconsistency in Veracity's tax filings. Veracity simply applied the statutory income allocation formula to the circumstances that existed at the different taxation year ends.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The judge's fundamental error&mdash;his starting assumption</UNDER></TI>
<P>19. The judge's reasons for finding Veracity's tax planning abusive indicate that he assumed from the outset that Veracity's capital gain should have been subject to provincial tax. He said:
<QUOTE><P>This is a simple case of a tax not being paid anywhere which ought to have been paid somewhere.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons, AR, p. 39, &para;29</P1></P>
<P>20. This incorrect and unsupported assumption derailed the judge from correctly applying the disciplined approach mandated by the Supreme Court of Canada and adopted by various appellate courts regarding the interpretation and application of a general anti-avoidance rule. The fiscal policy relied on in a GAAR analysis must be grounded in the provisions of the applicable tax law and not the judge's notion of what the law &ldquo;ought&rdquo; to be.</P>
<P>21. Contrary to the judge's assumption, there is no uniform system of provincial taxation in Canada that ensures all income is provincially taxed. The judge should have followed the reasoning of the appellate courts of Ontario and Alberta that acknowledged that lack of harmonization between provincial tax statutes may result in some amounts not being subject to provincial tax.</P>
<P>22. The following paragraphs contain:
<P1>(a) a summary of the analytical framework and basic principles for the application of a general anti-avoidance rule,</P1>
<P1>(b) a summary of the principles applicable to the BC GAAR; and</P1>
<P1>(c) a discussion of the judge's errors of law.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The interpretation and application of a general anti-avoidance rule</UNDER></TI>
<P>23. This is the first case to consider the BC GAAR and the first case to consider the GAAR of an &ldquo;agreeing province&rdquo;.</P>
<P>24. The BC GAAR is modelled on the federal GAAR in s. 245 of the federal Act. Although the two provisions are worded differently, their essential elements are the same. Therefore, it is appropriate to refer to the interpretation given to the federal GAAR in the extensive body of federal GAAR jurisprudence. This approach has been taken in other provincial GAAR cases.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Husky Energy Inc. v. Alberta</SOC><CITE>2012 ABCA 231</CITE></CASEREF>, leave to appeal to SCC refused (2013) 447 N.R. 400</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Canada Safeway Limited v. Alberta</SOC><CITE>2012 ABCA 232</CITE></CASEREF>, leave to appeal to SCC refused (2013) 447 N.R. 400</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Inter-Leasing. Inc. v. Ontario (Revenue)</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 575</CITE></CASEREF>, leave to appeal to SCC refused 2015 CarswellOnt 2996</P1></P>
<P>25. The GAAR does not interfere with the well-established principle that tax planning&mdash;arranging one's affairs so as to attract the least amount of tax&mdash;is a legitimate and accepted part of Canadian tax law. The GAAR applies only to tax avoidance that is abusive.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER>, &para;31, 35-6, 44&ndash;55</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Commissioners of Inland Revenue v. Duke of Westminster</SOC><CITE>[1936] A.C. 1</CITE><PAGENUM>p. 19</PAGENUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Copthorne Holdings Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 63</CITE><PARANUM>65&ndash;72</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>26. The GAAR is an exceptional provision of last resort. It may override any provision of the tax statute, even if the taxpayer has fully complied with its literal requirements, but only if the object, spirit or purpose of that provision has been frustrated or defeated.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER>, &para;21</P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Copthorne</EM></UNDER>, &para;66</P1></P>
<P>27. The Supreme Court of Canada has established the following analytical framework to determine the application of the GAAR:
<P1>1. Three requirements must be established to permit application of the GAAR:
<P2>(1) <EM>A tax benefit resulting from a transaction</EM> or part of a series of transactions [...];</P2>
<P2>(2) that the transaction is an <EM>avoidance transaction</EM> in the sense that it cannot be said to have been reasonably undertaken or arranged primarily for a <EM>bona fide purpose</EM> other than to obtain a tax benefit; and</P2>
<P2>(3) that there was <EM>abusive tax avoidance</EM> in the sense that it cannot be reasonably concluded that a tax benefit would be consistent with the object, spirit or purpose of the provisions relied upon by the taxpayer.</P2></P1>
<P1>2. The burden is on the taxpayer to refute (1) and (2), and on the Minister to establish (3).
<P2><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER>, &para;66 (statutory references omitted; emphasis in original)</P2></P1></P>
<P>28. For purposes of this appeal, Veracity admits that there was a &ldquo;tax benefit&rdquo; and an &ldquo;avoidance transaction&rdquo; for purposes of the BC GAAR. The sole issue for determination is whether Veracity misused or abused a provision of the BC Act.</P>
<P>29. In determining whether there has been abusive tax avoidance, it is necessary first to identify the specific statutory provisions that give rise to the tax benefit. Then, the misuse or abuse analysis is a two-step process: (1) interpret the provisions giving rise to the tax benefit to determine their object, spirit or purpose; and then (2) determine whether the transaction in issue frustrates that purpose.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER>, &para;44</P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Copthorne</EM></UNDER>, &para;69&ndash;72</P1></P>
<P>30. This determination is not a moral judgment. Nor can it be based on the judge's own theory of appropriate taxing policy. As the Supreme Court of Canada explains:
<QUOTE><P>...determining the rationale of the relevant provisions of the Act should not be conflated with a value judgment of what is right or wrong nor with theories about what tax law ought to be or ought to do.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Copthorne</EM></UNDER>, &para;70</P1>
<P1>See generally, on the court's role, <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. McLarty</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 26</CITE><PARANUM>75</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>31. The Crown must be precise in stating the purpose of the specific provisions alleged to give rise to the tax benefit, and in identifying the object or purpose of each provision that the Crown alleges has been abused or misused, referring not only to the statutory scheme but to any extrinsic material that informs the determination of the object and purpose of those provisions.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER>, &para;41, 64-65</P1></P>
<P>32. For a court to accept the existence of a fiscal policy advocated by the Crown, the policy must be anchored in the text of a specific provision of the relevant tax statute, not based on a vague &ldquo;overriding policy&rdquo; argument or moral opprobrium. In enacting the GAAR, Parliament intended to deter abusive tax avoidance while preserving legitimate tax planning, and therefore must be taken to have sought consistency, predictability and fairness in tax law.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER>, &para;1, 41-42</P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Copthorne</EM></UNDER>, &para;65&ndash;67</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lehigh Cement Ltd. v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2010 FCA 124</CITE><PARANUM>37</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>33. The GAAR cannot be used to override the explicit policy choice of a legislature. Even where a transaction takes advantage of a legislative gap, it is inappropriate to use the GAAR to fill that gap. To do so would place the formulation of tax policy in the hands of the judiciary, which was not intended by Parliament when the GAAR was enacted.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gwartz v. R.</SOC><CITE>2013 TCC 86</CITE><PARANUM>47</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Landrus v. R.</SOC><CITE>2008 TCC 274</CITE><PARANUM>124</PARANUM></CASEREF>, aff'd <UNDER>2009 FCA 113</UNDER></P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Lehigh</EM></UNDER>, &para;37</P1></P>
<P>34. The burden on the Crown to establish that a transaction is abusive tax avoidance is substantial. The abuse must be clear. If there is any doubt as to whether the transaction in issue is abusive, the taxpayer is entitled to the benefit of the doubt.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER>, &para;50, 66</P1></P>
<P>35. Examples drawn from leading federal and provincial GAAR cases demonstrate that the Crown's allegations of abuse have failed absent clear evidence that the purpose or policy of a specific provision has been frustrated or defeated.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER></P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Lehigh</EM></UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Imperial Oil Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2004 FCA 36</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER></P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER></P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER></P1></P>
<P>36. Veracity says that BC has not met&mdash;indeed has not approached&mdash;the high standard for applying the BC GAAR and the judge erred in finding there had been misuse or abuse of a provision of the BC Act.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The BC GAAR applies only to an abuse of a provision of the BC Act</UNDER></TI>
<P>37. A transaction or series of transactions will be subject to the BC GAAR, as it read at the relevant time, only if that transaction or series may reasonably be considered to result in a misuse or abuse of a provision of the BC Act. The relevant version of paragraph 68.1(1)(d) of the BC GAAR read as follows (emphasis added):
<QUOTE><P>In [section 68.1], &ldquo;avoidance transaction&rdquo;... does not include a transaction that may reasonably be considered</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>(d) to be a transaction that would not result, directly or indirectly, in a misuse of the provisions of <UNDER>this Act</UNDER> or an abuse having regard to the provisions of <UNDER>this Act</UNDER>, other than this section, read as a whole.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>38. The limited scope of the BC GAAR can be contrasted with the Ontario GAAR, which applies to a misuse or abuse of the Ontario Act or &ldquo;any Act or regulation of any jurisdiction that is relevant in computing tax or any amount payable by or refundable to a corporation under this Act or in determining any amount relevant for the purposes of that computation&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Corporations Tax Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, s. 5(3)(a)(iv)</P1>
<P1><EM>Taxation Act</EM>, S.O. 2007, c. 11, Sch. A, s. 110(4)(a)(iv)</P1></P>
<P>39. A similar issue of scope arose in the federal context where the Tax Court of Canada concluded in <UNDER><EM>Rousseau-Houle</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>Fredette</EM></UNDER> that because the federal GAAR referenced only the federal Act, an abuse of the federal Regulations was not subject to the GAAR. The federal GAAR has since been amended to refer to an abuse of the federal Regulations.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Rousseau-Houle c. R.</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>60 D.T.C. 3181</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2001 CanLII 695</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>TCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Fredette v. R.</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>55 D.T.C. 621</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2001 CanLII 625</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>TCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>40. The BC Act and the BC GAAR must be interpreted in light of BC's status as an agreeing province. BC entered into a tax collection agreement with Canada under which BC agreed, in exchange for Canada's administration and collection of its taxes, to levy tax using the <UNDER>same taxable base</UNDER> as Canada. The BC GAAR cannot override BC's Tax Collection Agreement or its consequences.
<P1>(a) The taxable base is &ldquo;taxable income&rdquo; as determined under the federal Act. BC makes no separate determination under the BC Act of &ldquo;taxable income&rdquo; or &ldquo;taxable income earned in the year in British Columbia&rdquo; that differs from the determination of &ldquo;taxable income&rdquo; or &ldquo;taxable income earned in the year in a province&rdquo; of the federal Act.</P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;Taxable income&rdquo; has the same meaning in the BC Act and the federal Act. BC levies tax under the BC Act on a corporation's &ldquo;taxable income earned in the year in British Columbia&rdquo; as determined in accordance with the regulations made under the federal Act.
<P2>Tax Collection Agreement, ss. 2(1)(c), 2(3), 19</P2>
<P2>BC Act, ss. 1 and 13.3</P2>
<P2>Peter Hogg, Joanne Magee and Jinyan Li, <EM>Principles of Canadian Income Tax Law</EM>, 8th ed (Toronto: Thomson Carswell, 2013), 1.3(f), 15.5(b)(vi)</P2></P1></P>
<P>41. The BC Act incorporates by reference certain provisions of the federal Act not relevant in this case. However, the BC Act does not incorporate by reference the provisions of the federal Act by which &ldquo;taxable income&rdquo; is calculated under the federal Act. Under the BC Tax Collection Agreement, BC accepts the federal determination of &ldquo;taxable income&rdquo; and the BC GAAR cannot be interpreted to undermine that agreement.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The judge erred in assuming there is a uniform system of provincial taxation</UNDER></TI>
<P>42. The judge made a fundamental legal error in conducting a GAAR analysis premised on the assumption that provincial tax &ldquo;ought to have been paid somewhere&rdquo;. Contrary to the judge's assumption, there is no uniform system of provincial taxation in Canada that ensures all income is provincially taxed.</P>
<P>43. Certain (&ldquo;agreeing&rdquo;) provinces, such as BC, have chosen to enter into tax collection agreements with Canada under which the provinces agree to use the same taxable base as Canada. This is intended to achieve &ldquo;simplicity, harmonization and uniformity&rdquo;, but only among the agreeing provinces and Canada.
<P1>Canada, <EM>Federal Administration of Provincial Taxes: New Directions</EM> (Ottawa: Department of Finance, January 2000), p. 15</P1>
<P1>Michelle Chan &amp; Charles Taylor, &ldquo;Provincial General Anti-Avoidance Rules and Governments' Responses to Interprovincial Tax Planning&rdquo; 2008 Conference Report (Toronto: Canadian Tax Foundation, 2009), p. 7: 4</P1>
<P1><EM>Federal Provincial Fiscal Arrangements Act</EM>, S.C. 1960-61, c. 58</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gendis Inc. v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2006 MBCA 58</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>44. If all of the provinces were &ldquo;agreeing provinces&rdquo; there would be perfect harmonization, but this has never been achieved. At the time of the transactions in issue in this case, seven provinces, including BC, were &ldquo;agreeing provinces&rdquo; with respect to corporate income tax. Quebec was not.</P>
<P>45. As a non-agreeing province, Quebec establishes its own tax base and tax rules that may differ from those of Canada and the other provinces. The Quebec Act does not incorporate by reference any sections of the federal Act, as this would be viewed &ldquo;as a surrender by the Quebec government of its fiscal autonomy.&rdquo;
<P1><UNDER>Finances Quebec, <EM>Simplification of the Tax System</EM></UNDER>, (Quebec: Biblioth&eg;que nationale du Qu&ea;bec, 2004), p. 16)</P1></P>
<P>46. The benefits of uniformity and the risks associated with different provincial tax rules within Canada have been known by provincial governments for more than a century. As recently as 2000, the Federal Department of Finance warned the provinces that the logical result of maintaining different tax bases is that some amounts will be taxed twice and other amounts will avoid tax completely. Yet certain provinces, including Quebec, have chosen to remain as non-agreeing provinces.
<P1>Ernest H. Smith, &ldquo;Allocating to Provinces the Taxable Income of Corporations: How the Federal-Provincial Allocation Rules Evolved,&rdquo; (1976), vol. 24, no. 5 Canadian Tax Journal, pp. 545-546</P1>
<P1>1940 <EM>Report of the Royal Commission on Dominion-Provincial Relations</EM> (&ldquo;Rowell-Sirois Commission&rdquo;), cited by Smith, pp. 547-548</P1>
<P1>1966 <EM>Report of the Royal Commission on Taxation</EM> (Ottawa: Royal Commission on Taxation, 1966) (&ldquo;Carter Commission&rdquo;), vol. 6, ch. 38, p. 188 and 194</P1>
<P1>Canada, Report of the Technical Committee on Business Taxation (Ottawa: Department of Finance, April 1998), &para;11.8</P1>
<P1><EM>Federal Administration of Provincial Taxes: New Directions</EM>, p. 13</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>GAAR cases that address inter-jurisdictional differences in tax laws</UNDER></TI>
<P>47. In considering the difference in tax laws between BC and Quebec in this case, the judge should have followed the reasoning and approach of the appellate courts in <UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER>, <UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER>. In those cases, the appellate courts of Ontario and Alberta acknowledged that lack of harmonization between provincial tax statutes may result in some amounts escaping provincial tax entirely, and they concluded that tax planning to take advantage of such a result is not abusive. If the judge had followed those decisions, he would have concluded that it was not abusive for Veracity to take advantage of the difference in the Quebec taxation year rule in its tax planning.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER></P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER></P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER></P1></P>
<P>48. In <UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER>, Alberta corporations claimed an Alberta deduction for interest paid on intercompany debt. The interest income on that debt was received by a related corporation with a taxable presence in Ontario but was not taxed by Ontario (or any province). The Alberta Minister of Finance asserted that the Alberta debtors' interest expense should be denied under the Alberta GAAR. The Alberta courts confirmed that the Alberta GAAR did not apply. The Alberta Court of Appeal said:
<QUOTE><P>...it would be a stretch to find abusive avoidance simply because a taxpayer took the benefit of another province's advantageous tax treatment.....This is especially so since differing provincial tax policies are a fundamental part of the Canadian federation.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER>, &para;49, affirming <UNDER>2011 ABQB 268</UNDER>, &para;59, 66, 72-73</P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER>, &para;45&ndash;51, 54-55, affirming <UNDER>2011 ABQB 329</UNDER>, &para;110</P1></P>
<P>49. In <UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER>, a BVI corporation established a taxable presence in Ontario by purchasing units of an Ontario limited partnership and received interest income from related corporations. The Ontario Minister of Revenue assessed the taxpayer on the basis that the interest income should be subject to Ontario tax and the judge upheld the Minister's assessment.</P>
<P>50. The Ontario Court of Appeal reversed the decision of the judge and concluded that the Ontario GAAR should not apply to tax the interest income. Although the taxpayer's tax minimization plan was designed to take advantage of a difference between Ontario and Alberta tax law, the Court found that the plan was not abusive. Justice Pardu acknowledged that:
<QUOTE><P>Differences in the thresholds for taxation as between the provinces or between a province and the federal government can give rise to gaps where some income escapes taxation and the other income may be subject to double taxation.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER>, &para;57</P1></P>
<P>51. In the international context, the non-taxation of income due to different taxation regimes was considered by the Federal Court of Appeal in <UNDER><EM>MIL</EM></UNDER>. The Court concluded that the object, spirit or purpose of the particular international treaty exemption relied on by the taxpayer had not been abused, and that the provision should not be interpreted differently because double non-taxation might result. The Court held that the federal GAAR applies to the incidence of Canadian taxation and is not concerned with whether a foreign country taxes the revenue not taxed by Canada. Similarly in this case, the BC GAAR should not be concerned with whether Quebec taxes Veracity's income not allocated to BC.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Canada v. MIL (Investments) S.A.</SOC><CITE>2007 FCA 236</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>52. The only other case to address a provincial GAAR is <UNDER><EM>OGT</EM></UNDER>. <UNDER><EM>OGT</EM></UNDER> was not applied by the Alberta Court of Appeal in <UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER> or <UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER>, and not even mentioned by the Ontario Court of Appeal in <UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER>. <UNDER><EM>OGT</EM></UNDER> has been criticized as being so flawed as to provide little guidance to other appellate courts.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>OGT Holdings Ltd. v. Quebec</SOC><CITE>2009 QCCA 191</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER>, &para;58</P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER>, &para;53</P1>
<P1>Ryan L. Morris and Andrew Etcovitch, &ldquo;Current Cases,&rdquo; (2009), vol. 57, no. 2 <EM>Canadian Tax Journal</EM>, 307&ndash;318</P1>
<P1>Robert Carvalho and Tim Clarke, &ldquo;Current Cases 2008-2009&rdquo;, <EM>2009 British Columbia Tax Conference</EM>, (Vancouver: Canadian Tax Foundation, 2009), 2: 1&ndash;30.</P1>
<P1>Don R. Sommerfeldt and Carman R. McNary, &ldquo;Post-<EM>Lipson</EM> GAAR Cases&rdquo;, CCH Tax Topics, No. 1944 (June 11, 2009).</P1>
<P1>Hugo Gravel, &ldquo;<CASEREF><SOC>L'Affaire OGT Holdings Ltd. c. SMRQ</SOC></CASEREF>: quand les tribunaux &ea;vitent la question&rdquo; (2009) 29: 2 Collection APFF.</P1>
<P1><UNDER>Joseph H. Takhmizdjian, &ldquo;Canada: Qu&ea;bec Court of Appeal Applies the GAAR&rdquo; 17 February 2009</UNDER></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The taxation year end provisions have not been abused</UNDER></TI>
<P>53. The burden is on the Crown to &ldquo;clearly&rdquo; demonstrate that Veracity abused a provision of the BC Act. The Crown cannot meet this high standard. To the contrary, Veracity satisfied the object, spirit and purpose of the provisions of the BC Act on which it relied.</P>
<P>54. The judge correctly identified, as the linchpin of this case, the right of a corporation to choose a different taxation year under the Quebec Act than under the BC Act. In the judge's words, the difference in Quebec law was the &ldquo;loophole&rdquo; employed:
<QUOTE><P>The entire plan pivoted on the anomalous provision in Quebec, prior to 2006, allowing a different year end to be selected for Quebec income tax purposes. Were it not for that, it would have been impossible to implement the Q-YES Plan.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons, AR, p. 45, &para;45</P1></P>
<P>55. However, the judge erred in law when he concluded that &ldquo;the Plan abused legislative provisions for taxation years and fiscal year ends&rdquo;.
<P1>(a) The first error was in treating the legislative provisions for fiscal and taxation year ends in the federal Act, the BC Act, and the Quebec Act, as though they were parts of a single harmonious statutory scheme that is subject to the BC GAAR. They are not. Each of these provisions must be considered separately.</P1>
<P1>(b) The second error was in considering the statutory provision relating to a taxation year in the Quebec Act. That provision is not subject to the BC GAAR.
<P2>Reasons, AR, p. 49, &para;57</P2></P1>
<P1>(c) The third error was in finding that the taxation year provision of the BC Act had been abused.</P1></P>
<P>56. Veracity was a BC corporation. Veracity chose June 30 as its taxation year end for federal tax purposes and, because of that choice, June 30 automatically became its taxation year end for BC tax purposes. This was statutorily mandated because the meanings of &ldquo;taxation year&rdquo; and &ldquo;fiscal period&rdquo; under the BC Act are defined as having the meanings in the federal Act.
<P1>BC Act, s. 1(1)</P1>
<P1>Federal Act, ss. 249(1), 249.1(1)</P1></P>
<P>57. The purpose of statutory requirement for a taxation year end is obvious. As the Supreme Court of Canada noted in <UNDER><EM>Copthorne</EM></UNDER>:
<QUOTE><P>In some cases the underlying rational of a provision would be no broader than the text itself. Provisions that may be so construed, having regard to their context and purpose, may support the argument that the text is conclusive because the text is consistent with and fully explains its underlying rationale.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Copthorne</EM></UNDER>, &para;110</P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER>, &para;61</P1></P>
<P>58. In order to collect revenue on a regular basis, governments require taxable income to be determined and reported annually. On incorporation, a corporation can choose any taxation year for purposes of the federal Act, subject to the limit that it be less than 53 weeks. Once selected, a corporation cannot change its taxation year without the permission of the Minister.
<P1>Federal Act, ss. 150(1)(a), 249(1), 249.1(1) and 249.1(7)</P1></P>
<P>59. The purpose of the taxation year provisions of the federal Act and, thus, the BC Act, is to ensure that a taxpayer measures income each year. Veracity met that purpose simply by adopting a taxation year end for federal (and thus BC purposes) and reporting its income annually.
<P1>Brian Arnold et al, <EM>Timing and Income Taxation</EM>, 2nd ed (Toronto: Canadian Tax Foundation, 2015), pp. 115&ndash;119</P1></P>
<P>60. The Crown cannot discharge its burden of demonstrating that the object, spirit or purpose of the BC taxation year rule has been frustrated. Veracity did not abuse the federal/BC taxation year rule&mdash;it functioned exactly as intended.</P>
<P>61. The tax benefit in this case arose because the Quebec Act allowed for a choice of taxation year that differed from that of the BC Act. Contrary to the judge's conclusion that the relevant legislation &ldquo;did not contemplate a taxpayer using different fiscal year ends in different jurisdictions for the same income in the same year&rdquo;, the Quebec Act contemplated exactly that.</P>
<P>62. Veracity chose to establish a presence <UNDER>in Quebec</UNDER> and then to choose a taxation year <UNDER>for Quebec purposes</UNDER> that was different than its federal/BC taxation year. Veracity's taxable income which, under the federal income allocation rules, was considered allocated to Quebec (and, therefore, was not allocated to BC for the purposes of the BC Act), was not subject to Quebec tax because of a timing difference arising from the substantive provisions of the Quebec Act. Whether there was an abuse of the Quebec taxation year rule is not relevant to the BC GAAR. Provisions of the Quebec Act are not subject to the BC GAAR.</P>
<P>63. It is never the role of a GAAR to override a specific tax policy choice made by a legislature. To do so inappropriately places the formulation of tax policy in the hands of the judiciary. Not only does the Crown seek to have this Court apply the BC GAAR to override a specific tax policy choice made by a legislature, it is a choice made by another province. That is not permitted under the BC GAAR.</P>
<P>64. The possibility of a different Quebec taxation year was eliminated in 2008 when Quebec amended its legislation to remove over 80 separate &ldquo;Quebec choices&rdquo; to better align provisions of the Quebec Act with the federal Act. One of these conforming changes (retroactive to 2006) was to require that a corporation's taxation year for Quebec purposes be the same as for federal purposes.</P>
<P>65. Where legislation permits a choice of different taxation years, a taxpayer does not abuse that legislation by taking advantage of that difference to avoid tax. In <UNDER><EM>Imperial Oil</EM></UNDER>, the Federal Court of Appeal held that the scheme of the large corporation tax provisions in issue &ldquo;virtually invited the use of different corporate fiscal year ends&rdquo; for different corporations within a related group. A corporation that took advantage of that loophole to avoid the federal large corporation tax was held not to have engaged in abusive tax avoidance under the federal GAAR. Similarly in this case, Veracity did not engage in abusive tax avoidance under the BC GAAR when it took advantage of a different Quebec year end.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Imperial Oil</EM></UNDER>, &para;79-80</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The income allocation rules have not been abused</UNDER></TI>
<P>66. The judge concluded that the transactions undertaken by the taxpayer abused &ldquo;the legislative provisions related to the allocation of taxable income between provinces&rdquo;. That conclusion cannot stand because it is not based on a purposive and contextual analysis of the federal/BC income allocation rules.</P>
<P>67. Under the federal income allocation rules, the taxable income earned in a province is allocated among provinces in which a corporation has a taxable presence (&ldquo;permanent establishment&rdquo;). Each &ldquo;agreeing province&rdquo;, including BC, accepts its income allocation under the federal rules as the taxable income upon which it may impose provincial corporate income tax. For BC, this agreement is set out in the BC Tax Collection Agreement and reflected in the BC Act.
<P1>Tax Collection Agreement, ss. 2(1)(c), 2(3), 19</P1>
<P1>BC Act, ss. 2(2), 13.3, 14(2)</P1>
<P1>Federal Act, Regulation 402(3)</P1></P>
<P>68. The non-agreeing provinces, such as Quebec, enact their own income allocation rules. While there are some differences between the Quebec income allocation rules and the federal/BC income allocation rules, none are relevant in this case. In this case, for all practical purposes the federal/BC income allocation rules and Quebec income allocation rules are identical and functioned as intended.
<P1>Smith, pp. 560, 563-564</P1>
<P1>Paul Bleiwas and John Hutson, <EM>Taxation of Private Corporations and Their Shareholders</EM>, 4th ed (Toronto: Canadian Tax Foundation, 2010), p. 14: 15</P1></P>
<P>69. As described above, the income allocation rules are formulaic. These rules, when applied to Veracity for its federal/BC taxation year ended June 30, 2003, resulted in approximately 10% of its taxable income being allocated to BC. Veracity had a taxable presence in Quebec such that its taxable income not allocated to BC might have been taxed in Quebec. Had Quebec required that Veracity's taxation year for Quebec purposes be the same as it was for federal/BC purposes, approximately 90% of Veracity's taxable income would have been subject to Quebec tax.</P>
<P>70. Veracity's taxable capital gain was subject to limited provincial taxation. This was not a result of any differences between the income allocation rules of BC and Quebec. Those rules were substantially the same. The result arose because the rules applied at different times to different facts due to Veracity's different Quebec taxation year.</P>
<P>71. Veracity agrees with the judge that the purpose of the income allocation rules is to provide a basis for imposing tax liability in the &ldquo;appropriate province&rdquo;. However, Veracity disagrees with the judge's acceptance of the Crown's assertion that the income allocation rules are designed to prevent both the over taxation and the under-taxation of income earned by a corporation which has a taxable presence in more than one province.
<P1>Reasons, AR, p. 47, &para;50</P1></P>
<P>72. On the contrary, it is not the purpose of the income allocation rules to ensure that provincial tax is <UNDER>actually imposed</UNDER> on taxable income allocated to a province. This distinction between allocation and taxation is critical. Whether taxable income allocated to a province is taxed in that province is a matter for each province to determine. This is clear from the statutory scheme of the federal Act of which the income allocation rules are a part and the legislative history of those rules.</P>
<P>73. Under the federal Act, a corporation's tax is reduced by 10% to the extent that it has &ldquo;taxable income earned in a province&rdquo; (that is, in <UNDER>any</UNDER> province). That reduction, called the &ldquo;federal abatement&rdquo; gives the provinces &ldquo;room&rdquo; to levy provincial corporate taxes. The amount of the abatement is the same regardless of the actual provincial tax imposed.
<P1>Federal Act, ss. 123(1), 124(1), Part IV of the Regulations</P1></P>
<P>74. Each province may then impose its own income tax on a corporation's taxable income attributable to a &ldquo;permanent establishment&rdquo; in the province. For agreeing provinces, the federal income allocation rules prescribe how a taxpayer's &ldquo;taxable income earned in the year in a province&rdquo; is determined. As explained above, non-agreeing provinces, such as Quebec, enact their own rules.</P>
<P>75. The federal income allocation rules have been a feature of the federal Act since before the tax collection agreements. Their function is to give each province &ldquo;room&rdquo; to tax income earned in a province and to ensure that no income is taxed in more than one province. They do not and cannot ensure that a province does in fact levy tax. As the assistant deputy federal Minister of Finance said in 1955:
<QUOTE><P>The objective of the federal rules is to create scope for a provincial tax and let them do what they like.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Roger Letourneau, E.H. Ambrose, J.C. Wilson, and A.K. Eaton, &ldquo;Allocation of Corporate Profits&mdash;Federal-Quebec Overlapping,&rdquo; Report of the Proceedings of the Ninth Tax Conference, 1955 Conference Report (Toronto: Canadian Tax Foundation, 1956), 103&ndash;125</P1>
<P1>Smith, p. 562&ndash;564</P1>
<P1>Bleiwas and Hutson, p. 14:12</P1></P>
<P>76. If all provinces were agreeing provinces, there would be <UNDER>no overlap</UNDER> between the provincial tax bases. In the Parliamentary debates at the time the income allocation rules were first adopted, the federal Minister of Finance confirmed:
<QUOTE><P>If these rules for allocating income were adopted by all provinces, there would be eliminated the tendency which prevailed at times in the past for various provincial governments to impose tax, in the aggregate, on more than the total income of corporation carrying on business in several provinces.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Canada, House of Commons, Official Report of Debates (Hansard), 20th Pari, 3rd Sess, Vol 6 (9 July 1947) at 5313 (Hon Douglas Abbott).</P1></P>
<P>77. It is one thing to ensure that the same taxable income is only allocated to one province, and therefore is not taxed by more than one province (ultimately preventing double taxation). It is quite another thing to try to ensure that the income <UNDER>will be taxed</UNDER> by a province. That has not been achieved, and it has not been an objective of the allocation rules or the federal-provincial collection agreements. Gaps in taxation may still exist as a result of different provincial fiscal policies.</P>
<P>78. While agreeing provinces levy tax on the same tax base as Canada, each province will make policy decisions as to whether to provide certain tax incentives or preferences. For example, BC provides preferences using provincial tax credits and tax rebates. Non-agreeing provinces, such as Quebec, make their own fiscal policy decisions regarding the provincial tax base as well as tax incentives and preferences. These provincial fiscal policy choices can result in taxable income which has been allocated to a province being lightly taxed or not taxed at all.</P>
<P>79. The Alberta Court of Appeal in <UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER> confirmed that where the purpose of a provision is to relieve against double taxation, that does not mean the purpose is to ensure that a minimum level of tax is paid. One issue in those cases was the purpose of the federal Act provision (s. 112(1)) that allows a corporation that receives a taxable dividend to take an equal offsetting deduction, in effect receiving the dividend tax free. The Crown argued that while the purpose of the dividend deduction was to preclude double taxation, the purpose had been frustrated because the income out of which the dividend was paid had not been subject to any provincial taxation. The Alberta Court of Appeal rejected the Crown's argument that the purpose was also to ensure a minimum level of tax, in reliance on the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <UNDER><EM>Antosko</EM></UNDER>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Antosko v. R.</SOC><CITE>[1994] 2 S.C.R. 312</CITE><PAGENUM>pp. 331-332</PAGENUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER>, 50&ndash;56</P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER>, &para;43&ndash;51</P1></P>
<P>80. The purpose of the federal/BC income allocation rules is to prevent overlapping allocation which would lead to double taxation. The Crown in this case seeks to engraft an additional purpose onto the rules&mdash;that the result arising under those rules should not be respected where taxable income allocated under those rules is exempt from provincial taxation.</P>
<P>81. A similar attempt to engraft an additional purpose onto a provision was made by the Crown in <UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER>. The Crown argued under the Alberta GAAR that the provision of the federal Act (s. 20(1)(c)) that was relied on by the taxpayers to support an interest deduction had been frustrated because the corresponding receipt of interest was not taxed in Ontario. The Court rejected this argument:
<QUOTE><P>Had Alberta intended the purpose of its counterpart provision to section 20(1)(c) to depend on the circumstances of other taxpayers (the lenders), it could have used language denying an interest deduction when the lender's interest income was not taxable.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER>, &para;45</P1></P>
<P>82. The Crown's theory of the purpose of the federal/BC income allocation rules is not supported by their text, their context or their legislative history. To the contrary, the federal/BC income allocation rules applied to Veracity as intended. Taxable income was allocated in accordance with Veracity's taxable presence in BC and Quebec. Taxable income allocable to Quebec under the federal income allocation rules (and not allocated to BC) was not subject to Quebec tax because Quebec permitted Veracity to choose a different taxation year for Quebec purposes, not because there was any abuse of the income allocation rules. Veracity satisfied the object, spirit and purpose of the income allocation rules.</P>
<P>83. If Quebec had required Veracity to have the same taxation year for Quebec purposes as for federal/BC purposes, Veracity's taxable income that was allocable to Quebec under the federal rules would have been subject to Quebec tax. There can be no misuse or abuse of the BC income allocation rules that turns on whether taxable income not allocated to BC is taxed in another province. The appellate court decisions in <UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER>, <UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER>, <UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>MIL</EM></UNDER> all confirm that the application of a GAAR does not depend on whether income not taxed in the jurisdiction covered by that GAAR is taxed somewhere else.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>Section 85 and the rules for calculating taxable income have not been abused</UNDER></TI>
<P>84. The judge erred in accepting the Crown's submission that the federal Act provisions relevant in determining taxable income (s. 3, 38, 39 and 40 and s. 85) were misused or abused. The judge made several errors in arriving at this conclusion.</P>
<P>85. These provisions are not subject to the BC GAAR because they are not provisions of the BC Act and are not incorporated by reference into the BC Act.
<P1>See Leah Plumridge and Daniel Sandler, &ldquo;Quebec &ldquo;year-end shuffle&rdquo; subject to BC GAAR: <CASEREF><SOC>Veracity Capital Corporation v. Canada (National Revenue)</SOC><CITE>2015 BCSC 2278</CITE></CASEREF>&rdquo; EY Commentary 2016-001, January 14, 2016</P1></P>
<P>86. Each of these provisions was relevant only in so far as they were elements in the determination of Veracity's taxable income under the federal Act. When BC agreed under the BC Tax Collection Agreement to levy tax on its allocated share of taxable income as determined under the federal Act, BC agreed to accept the federal determination of taxable income. The BC GAAR cannot be applied to alter this determination, or any of its statutory elements.
<P1>Janette Pantry, &ldquo;The Role of the Provincial General Anti-Avoidance Rules in Interprovincial Taxation,&rdquo; 2013 Conference Report, (Toronto: Canadian Tax Foundation, 2014), 36: 13-14</P1></P>
<P>87. In any event, the Crown has never alleged that Veracity's capital gain or its taxable income was incorrectly determined. The fact that Veracity did not pay provincial tax on a certain portion of its taxable income had nothing to do with s. 85 of the federal Act, or the calculation of Veracity's capital gain under the federal Act. If no s. 85 election had been made, Veracity's cost of the ALI shares would have been their fair market value as of the date on which Veracity acquired them, and Veracity would have had little or no capital gain when it later sold the ALI shares. There was no &ldquo;tax benefit&rdquo; to Veracity from the s. 85 elections or the federal Act provisions under which Veracity's capital gain was determined. Therefore there could be no abuse of those provisions.</P>
<P>88. The judge also erred in finding that s. 85 was &ldquo;intended only to preserve and defer tax&rdquo;. The purpose of s. 85 is to allow a taxpayer to defer the recognition of a gain on the disposition of property, so that the deferred gain may be realized by the transferee upon a subsequent disposition of the property. Nothing in s. 85 ensures or is intended to ensure that the deferred gain is taxed at some later time, or at any time. Any number of intervening events, planned or unplanned, could preclude that result. For example, the deferred gain might be reduced if values shift or, even if the full deferred gain is realized, it may be sheltered by losses or an exemption. In this case, s. 85 worked exactly as it was intended to work. The capital gain that would have been realized by Mr. Peet and Pi Capital if no s. 85 election had been made was deferred, and the entire deferred gain was realized by Veracity on the sale of the ALI shares.
<P1>Reasons, AR, p. 48, &para;53.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Evans v. R.</SOC><CITE>2005 TCC 684</CITE><PARANUM>27&ndash;29</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>89. The judge's incorrect determination of the purpose of s. 85 led him to err further in relying on <UNDER><EM>OGT</EM></UNDER>, a case of doubtful authority (see para 52 above) that in any event is distinguishable on its facts. In <UNDER><EM>OGT</EM></UNDER>, a Quebec corporate taxpayer transferred shares to an Ontario corporate taxpayer in exchange for shares. An election was made under s. 518 of the Quebec Act (the analogue to s. 85) to defer the capital gain for Quebec purposes that would otherwise be realized. No &ldquo;rollover&rdquo; election was made under s. 85 of the federal Act and the Quebec taxpayer realized a capital gain for federal purposes. At that time, it was possible to make a Quebec &ldquo;rollover&rdquo; election that differed from the federal election although the Quebec Act has since been amended.</P>
<P>90. When the Ontario corporate taxpayer sold the shares, it realized no capital gain for federal purposes but it also realized no capital gain for Ontario purposes because the applicable Ontario rule was harmonized with the federal rule. Thus the capital gain that was deferred for Quebec purposes was never realized for any provincial purpose and was not subject to provincial tax.</P>
<P>91. The Quebec Court of Appeal found this to be an abuse of s. 518 of the Quebec Act. The taxpayer had used a Quebec &ldquo;rollover&rdquo; provision to avoid Quebec tax. The remedy under the Quebec GAAR was to deny the effect of the Quebec election. In effect, the Quebec GAAR applied to eliminate the taxpayer's ability to access a Quebec difference.</P>
<P>92. Unlike <UNDER><EM>OGT</EM></UNDER>, Veracity did not use a BC &ldquo;rollover&rdquo; provision that differed from a federal &ldquo;rollover&rdquo; provision because no such BC difference exists. The result of the federal s. 85 elections in this case was the same federally and provincially. Accordingly, <UNDER><EM>OGT</EM></UNDER> has no application in this case.</P>
<P>93. The sections of the federal Act relevant in determining Veracity's taxable income did not give rise to the provincial tax benefit at issue, are not subject to the BC GAAR and, in any event, operated exactly as they were supposed to. For all these reasons, the judge erred in finding that there was abuse of these provisions under the BC GAAR.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Conclusion</UNDER></TI>
<P>94. The Supreme Court of Canada has repeatedly stated that any allegation of abusive tax avoidance must be grounded in the textual, contextual and purposive analysis of the relevant statutory provisions, it cannot be based on a tax policy not found in the relevant legislation.</P>
<P>95. Here, the judge's conclusion was based on his unfounded assumption that all of Veracity's income &ldquo;ought&rdquo; to have been subject to provincial tax &ldquo;somewhere&rdquo;. This premise is not found in the provisions of the BC Act or any other provincial statute and is impugned by concepts of provincial sovereignty. Each province has the right to set its own tax policy. The natural and foreseeable result of those provincial choices is the potential for gaps between the tax nets of the provinces.</P>
<P>96. Veracity took advantage of the Quebec difference. Provisions of the Quebec Act are not subject to the BC GAAR and Veracity's choice was not abusive of the BC Act. As the appellate courts of Ontario and Alberta found in <UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER>, <UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER>, taking advantage of favourable tax treatment in another province is not abusive.</P>
<P>97. Quebec responded to the perceived abuse in this case by eliminating the ability to choose a different tax year end for Quebec purposes. That was a legislative remedy within the jurisdiction of the Quebec legislature. It is not the function of the BC GAAR.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>98. The appellant seeks an Order:</P>
<P>The appellant requests that the appeal be allowed, with costs throughout.</P>
<P>99. All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
