<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>The appellant Veracity is a B.C. corporation incorporated by a B.C. resident individual as part of the Q-Yes plan, a tax plan intended to avoid B.C. income tax that would have been payable in respect of a $19.4 million capital gain realized on a share sale. The Q-Yes plan avoided B.C. tax by engineering an allocation of taxable income to Quebec for B.C. tax purposes. The plan resulted in a 90% reduction of the B.C. tax that would ordinarily have been payable.</P>
<P>The B.C. <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.B.C. 1996, c. 215 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;B.C. Act&rdquo;)</BOLD> levies provincial income tax on corporations that maintain a permanent establishment in B.C. at any time during a taxation year. Tax is paid on the corporation's taxable income earned in the year in British Columbia, an amount determined under an allocation formula found in the federal <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp.) (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Federal Act&rdquo;)</BOLD> and <EM>Income Tax Regulations</EM>, C.R.C., c. 945 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Federal Regulations&rdquo;).</BOLD> Those provisions are intended to prevent both the over-taxation and the under-taxation of income earned by a corporation with a presence in more than one province in a year.</P>
<P>Section 68.1 of the B.C. Act (the <BOLD>&ldquo;BC GAAR&rdquo;)</BOLD> provides that where a tax benefit results from one or more avoidance transactions, the tax consequences to a taxpayer must be determined so as to deny the tax benefit that results from those avoidance transactions. The trial judge found that the Q-Yes plan contained at least four avoidance transactions, undertaken primarily to avoid B.C. tax and which resulted in an abuse of the provisions of the B.C. Act by permitting Veracity to avoid $1,175 million of B.C. tax on $8.7 million of its taxable income.</P>
<P>In finding abusive tax avoidance, the trial judge identified the object and spirit of the provisions that Veracity relied on to obtain that tax benefit. He found that the avoidance transactions were inconsistent with that object and spirit and that the abuse of those provisions is clear. He made no error in doing so.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>1. The facts as stated by the appellant are substantially accurate but are incomplete for purposes of this appeal. The respondent relies on the facts as stated below.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>The ALI Technologies Takeover</TI>
<P>2. ALI was incorporated on April 11, 1988. It grew into a leading vendor of picture archiving and communications systems for the digital management of radiological images. In 1993, Greg Peet was recruited to become ALI's CEO.
<P1>Reasons for Judgment of Macintosh J. (&ldquo;Reasons&rdquo;), paras. 9-10 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 32)</P1>
<P1>Partial Agreed Statement of Facts (&ldquo;PASF&rdquo;), paras. 1&ndash;15 (Joint Appeal Book)</P1></P>
<P>3. ALI attracted the attention of McKesson Corporation. On May 1, 2002, McKesson informed ALI that it was prepared to make a formal takeover bid subject to the execution of a support agreement with ALI and of lock-up agreements with ALI's principal shareholders. On that day, McKesson and 646543 BC entered into a support agreement with ALI and into lock-up agreements with ALI's principal shareholders, including Peet. The lock-up agreement unconditionally and irrevocably committed Peet to accept 646543 BC's offer.
<P1>Reasons, para. 10 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 32)</P1>
<P1>PASF, paras. 21&ndash;25 (Joint Appeal Book)</P1></P>
<P>4. As of May 1, 2002, Peet and his family, directly and through his holding company Pi Capital, held 714,207 common shares of ALI. Peet held 428,907 ALI shares directly outside his RRSP (and not in trust for any other person), and Pi Capital held 110,600. Peet held a further 218,400 ALI options.
<P1>Reasons, para. 11 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 33)</P1>
<P1>PASF, paras. 26-27 (Joint Appeal Book)</P1></P>
<P>5. On May 30, 2002, 646543 BC issued its takeover bid for all outstanding ALI shares.
<P1>Reasons, para. 10 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 32)</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Q-Yes Plan</TI>
<P>6. Anticipating a significant capital gain from the sale of his ALI shares, Peet approached KPMG for tax planning advice. KPMG provided Peet with eight possible tax saving strategies including the Q-Yes plan. KPMG divided the strategies into categories labelled &ldquo;standard&rdquo; and &ldquo;innovative&rdquo; and attached a risk assessment to each strategy. It labelled the Q-Yes plan as an innovative strategy presenting a moderate risk.
<P1>Reasons, paras. 13 and 18 (Appeal Record Tab 4, pp. 33-34)</P1></P>
<P>7. In an engagement letter issued June 6, 2002, KPMG confirmed Peet's instructions to proceed with the Q-Yes plan. In the engagement letter, KPMG committed to provide comments and suggested steps to effect the tax plan, including by determining the appropriate year ends and necessary investments, by preparing a detailed instruction letter outlining the necessary steps and transactions to implement the plan, and by generally managing the implementation of the transactions.
<P1>Reasons, para. 15 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 33)</P1></P>
<P>8. KPMG's fee for preparing and implementing the Q-Yes plan was $110,000. The fee was contingent and was subject to reduction to as little as $40,000 if a tax authority successfully challenged the plan.
<P1>Reasons, para. 16 (Appeal Record Tab 4, pp. 33-34)</P1></P>
<P>9. The following transactions were undertaken pursuant to KPMG's plan:
<P1>1. <UNDER>Incorporation of Veracity</UNDER>
<P2>a. Veracity was incorporated on June 10, 2002. Veracity was incorporated because the Q-Yes tax benefit is available only to a corporation, and because the plan required a corporation without preexisting income or expenses that would be malleable for provincial income allocation purposes.
<P3>Testimony of Greg Peet (&ldquo;Peet Testimony&rdquo;), Transcript of proceedings, p. 83 line 37 to p. 84 line 47 (Joint Appeal Book)</P3></P2>
<P2>b. Veracity selected a June 30 fiscal period end for federal and B.C. tax purposes. Its first B.C. taxation year ran from June 10 to 30, 2002.</P2>
<P2>c. Veracity selected a June 30 federal/B.C. fiscal period end to defer reporting the Taxable Gain by a calendar year so that the Taxable Gain would not be reported in B.C. until after Gaz Metro had allocated revenues and salaries that would cause Veracity's taxable income to be allocated to Quebec.
<P3>Peet Testimony, p. 95 lines 26&ndash;47 and p. 96 lines 1&ndash;14 (Joint Appeal Book)</P3></P2>
<P2>d. Peet and his spouse were appointed Veracity's directors.</P2></P1>
<P1>2. <UNDER>Transfer of ALI shares to Veracity</UNDER>
<P2>a. On June 14, 2002, Peet and Pi Capital transferred to Veracity 539,507 ALI shares, representing all of the ALI shares that Peet &ldquo;freely&rdquo; held.</P2>
<P2>b. Veracity, Peet, and Pi Capital elected to transfer the ALI shares on a tax-deferred basis pursuant to s. 85 of the Federal Act. The shares were transferred at their adjusted cost base.</P2></P1>
<P1>3. <UNDER>Veracity sold the ALI shares</UNDER>
<P2>a. Subsequently, Veracity accepted 646543 BC's offer to purchase the ALI shares. On July 11, 2002 Veracity received cash proceeds of $24,468,554.50 for the ALI shares.</P2></P1>
<P1>4. <UNDER>Veracity paid director's fees in B.C.</UNDER>
<P2>a. On July 11, 2002, Veracity paid $1,000 each to Peet and his spouse as director's fees. This was done to ensure that when income was reported in Quebec 100% of the income would be allocated to B.C.
<P3>Peet Testimony, p. 108 lines 19&ndash;32 (Joint Appeal Book)</P3></P2>
<P2>b. Veracity then immediately transferred the remaining $23,466,554.60 from its bank account to Pi Capital, recording the transfer as an interest-free demand loan. This was done to ensure that Veracity did not earn interest income in B.C. that would increase the allocation of taxable income to B.C. for the B.C. taxation year ending June 30, 2003.
<P3>Peet Testimony p. 89 line 38 to p. 90 line 14 (Joint Appeal Book)</P3></P2></P1>
<P1>5. <UNDER>Veracity purchased units of Gaz Metro</UNDER>
<P2>a. Between July 22 and 29, 2002, Veracity purchased 15,000 units of Gaz Metro for $266,337.</P2>
<P2>b. Gaz Metro was a publicly-traded limited partnership with a permanent establishment in Quebec. Gaz Metro was a regulated natural gas utility carrying on business in Quebec.</P2>
<P2>c. Gaz Metro had a September 30 year-end and was expected to allocate proportionate shares of gross revenues, salaries, and wages to Veracity at that year-end.</P2>
<P2>d. The purchase of Gaz Metro units resulted in Veracity having a permanent establishment in Quebec for purposes of the Federal Act and the Federal Regulations. The purchase also resulted in Veracity maintaining an &ldquo;establishment&rdquo; in Quebec under the Quebec <EM>Taxation Act</EM>, C.Q.L.R. c. I-3 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Quebec Act&rdquo;</BOLD>). Accordingly, Veracity became liable to Quebec income tax.</P2>
<P2>e. Veracity purchased the Gaz Metro units because KPMG advised it to do so as a critically-important ingredient of the Q-Yes plan. Mr. Peet was not aware of Gaz Metro as a potential investment apart from it being used as a key step in the Q-Yes plan.</P2>
<P2>f. Acquiring units of Gaz Metro provided Veracity with a means to allocate taxable income (including the Taxable Gain) to Quebec for B.C. tax purposes, thus avoiding B.C. tax otherwise payable.</P2>
<P2>g. Gaz Metro was carefully chosen because (a) it was a partnership rather than a corporation, and would give rise to a permanent establishment in Quebec; (b) its year-end fell between Veracity's Quebec and B.C. fiscal year-ends; and (c) it offered security and liquidity and minimized the commercial risk associated with obtaining the tax benefit.
<P3>Peet Testimony, p. 116, lines 8&ndash;25, p. 118 line 20 to p. 119 line 25.</P3></P2></P1>
<P1>6. <UNDER>Veracity selected different fiscal periods for Quebec and B.C. tax purposes</UNDER>
<P2>a. Veracity selected an August 31 fiscal year end for Quebec income tax purposes. Its first taxation year for Quebec income tax purposes ran from June 14 to August 31, 2002.</P2>
<P2>b. Selecting different fiscal period ends in B.C. and Quebec enabled Veracity to obtain the benefit of avoiding B.C. tax without being liable for Quebec tax on that same income. Veracity reported the Taxable Gain in Quebec at a time when it would not have any Quebec tax liability because Gaz Metro had not yet allocated any revenues or wages.</P2>
<P2>c. Veracity could not have obtained the benefit of avoiding B.C. tax without incurring a corresponding Quebec tax liability if it had chosen the same fiscal period in both provinces. With a common fiscal period, Veracity would have been taxed on 100% of the Taxable Gain in one province or the other:
<P3>i. If June 30 was the common fiscal period end, then the Taxable Gain would have been reported as of June 30, 2003 in both provinces, the Quebec allocation formula would have allocated 89.8% of its taxable income to Quebec, and the federal formula would have allocated 10.2% to B.C.</P3>
<P3>ii. If August 31 was the common fiscal period end, then the Taxable Gain would have been reported as of August 31, 2002 in both provinces and the federal allocation formula would have allocated 100% to B.C.</P3></P2></P1>
<P1>7. <UNDER>Veracity acquired additional units in Gaz Metro</UNDER>
<P2>a. From September 10 to 13, 2002, Veracity acquired an additional 30,000 units of Gaz Metro for $547,422. By September 13, 2002, Veracity held 45,000 Gaz Metro units with a total cost of $813,759.</P2>
<P2>b. The primary purpose for acquiring additional Gaz Metro units in September 2002 was to further avoid B.C. tax under the Q-Yes plan. In August 2002, Peet learned that Veracity had not invested as much in Gaz Metro as KPMG had expected. KPMG provided him with worksheets showing that the B.C. tax could be reduced by a further $150,000 through increasing the Gaz Metro investment to $800,000. A $150,000 reduction in B.C. tax equated to an immediate 27.4% return on the additional Gaz Metro investment of $547,422.</P2>
<P2>c. Acquiring 45,000 Gaz Metro units permitted Veracity to avoid $1,175,249 of B.C. tax with minimal investment risk. That saving equates to a 150% one-year return on the $813,759 investment. By contrast, the Gaz Metro units generated $241,000 of income over four years, representing a cumulative return of 29.6% and an average annual return of 7.6%. The immediate tax benefit of the investment outweighed the investment return by five-to-one.</P2>
<P2>d. Veracity bought all of the Gaz Metro units primarily in order to maximize the tax reduction under the Q-Yes plan.</P2>
<P2>Reasons, paras. 19 and 21&ndash;26 (Appeal Record Tab 4, pp. 34&ndash;36 and 37-38)</P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Veracity's Tax Reporting in B.C. and Quebec</TI>
<P>10. On disposing of the ALI shares to 646543 BC, Veracity realized a capital gain of $19,419,982 of which 50%, being $9,709,991, is the Taxable Gain.
<P1>PASF, paras. 33&ndash;36 (Joint Appeal Book)</P1></P>
<P>11. In its federal/B.C. income tax return for the taxation year ending June 30, 2002, Veracity reported no income, as it had not disposed of the ALI shares by that date.
<P1>PASF, para. 37 (Joint Appeal Book)</P1></P>
<P>12. In its Quebec income tax return for the year ending August 31, 2002, Veracity reported taxable income of $9,686,591, including the Taxable Gain. Veracity reported that 100% of its business was carried on in B.C. because 100% of the wages and salaries paid in that period (the director's fees) were paid in B.C. and it had no gross revenues. As a result, Veracity owed no Quebec income tax.
<P1>PASF, paras. 38&ndash;40 (Joint Appeal Book)</P1></P>
<P>13. In its federal/B.C. income tax return for the taxation year ending June 30, 2003, Veracity reported taxable income of $9,698,646, including the Taxable Gain. Veracity allocated $8,705,551 (89.8%) of that taxable income to Quebec and $993,095 (10.2%) to B.C. Veracity paid $134,068 of B.C. income tax.
<P1>PASF, paras. 41&ndash;43 (Joint Appeal Book)</P1></P>
<P>14. In the result, Veracity paid provincial income tax on only $993,095 of the Taxable Gain. $8,705,551 was neither reported as taxable nor taxed in any province.
<P1>Reasons, para. 20 (Appeal Record Tab 4, pp. 36-37)</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The reassessment and the appeal</TI>
<P>15. The Minister of National Revenue (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Minister&rdquo;)</BOLD> applied the BC GAAR to allocate 100% of Veracity's taxable income in the taxation year ending June 30, 2003 to B.C. The Minister increased Veracity's taxable income earned in that year in British Columbia by $8,705,551 (the amount previously allocated to Quebec) and assessed additional B.C. income tax of $1,175,249.</P>
<P>16. The appellant appealed the assessment to the Supreme Court under s. 42 of the BC Act. The trial judge dismissed the appeal.</P>
<P>17. The trial judge based his decision on the following findings of fact:
<P1>a. The reason for Veracity employing the Q-Yes plan was to avoid income tax that would otherwise have been paid in B.C.
<P2>Reasons, para. 20 (Appeal Record Tab 4, pp. 36-37)</P2></P1>
<P1>b. Veracity obtained a B.C. tax benefit from the Q-Yes Plan. That tax benefit was avoiding $1,175,249 of B.C. income tax that would have been payable on its taxable income of $9,698,646 in the 2003 taxation year had it not undertaken the Q-Yes Plan.
<P2>Reasons, paras. 28 and 33&ndash;35 (Appeal Record Tab 4, pp. 39&ndash;41)</P2></P1>
<P1>c. The Q-Yes plan comprised a &ldquo;series of transactions&rdquo; at common law. The transactions were undertaken pursuant to a detailed instruction letter prepared by KPMG and they operated together to produce the tax benefit.
<P2>Reasons, para. 39 (Appeal Record Tab 4, pp. 42&ndash;45)</P2></P1>
<P1>d. The series contained at least four avoidance transactions: (1) the incorporation of Veracity; (2) the transfer of ALI shares to Veracity by Peet and Pi Capital; (3) the acquisition of units in Gaz Metro; and (4) the selection and filing on the basis of different fiscal periods for federal/B.C. tax purposes on one hand and for Quebec purposes on the other.
<P2>Reasons, para. 40 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 45)</P2></P1>
<P1>e. The primary purpose for each of those four transactions was to obtain the benefit of avoiding B.C. income tax.
<P2>Reasons, paras. 41&ndash;45 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 45)</P2></P1>
<P1>f. Each transaction except for the ALI share sale and the Gaz Metro revenue and wages allocation was probably an avoidance transaction, although it was not necessary to extend the analysis beyond the four identified above.
<P2>Reasons, para. 46 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p.46)</P2></P1></P>
<P>18. The trial judge rejected the appellant's attempts to justify the purchase of Gaz Metro units as primarily investment-driven.
<P1>Reasons, paras. 21&ndash;27 (Appeal Record Tab 4, pp.37&ndash;38)</P1></P>
<P>19. In determining that the avoidance transactions resulted in a misuse or abuse of the provisions of the B.C. Act, the trial judge held that:
<P1>a. Abusive tax avoidance results when: (1) the transaction achieves an outcome the statutory provision was intended to prevent; (2) the transaction defeats the underlying rationale of the provision; or (3) the transaction circumvents the provision in a manner that frustrates or defeats its object, spirit or, purpose. Having regard to those three criteria, the Q-Yes plan implemented by Veracity resulted in abusive tax avoidance.
<P2>Reasons, paras. 47&ndash;49 (Appeal Record Tab 4, pp.46&ndash;47)</P2></P1>
<P1>b. The relevant legislation includes provisions of the B.C. Act establishing the basis for Veracity's liability to B.C. tax as well as provisions of the Federal Act and Regulations incorporated into or adopted by the B.C. Act for computing tax liability under the B.C. Act. The legislative scheme intends that capital gains earned in Canada by corporations be taxed as income by the provinces based on an allocation formula designed to prevent both the over-taxation and the under-taxation of corporate income earned in multiple provinces.
<P2>Reasons, para. 50 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 47)</P2></P1>
<P1>c. The Q-Yes plan abused s. 85 of the Federal Act because that provision is a rollover provision intended to preserve and defer tax and the Q-Yes plan used it to avoid the tax completely. Section 85 was used to put the ALI shares, and the related gain, in the hands of a taxpayer who could then avoid B.C. tax completely on 90% of the taxable gain. Using a tax deferral provision in that way was not within the object and spirit of the provision.
<P2>Reasons, paras. 53-54 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 48)</P2></P1>
<P1>d. The Q-Yes plan abused the B.C. and Federal Act provisions for determining income, taxable income and taxable income earned in a year in British Columbia. The plan computed a taxable capital gain which was to be included in income but which was not taxed notwithstanding an intention in both Acts that taxable capital gains be subject to taxation like ordinary income. Transactions resulting in capital gains which avoid tax completely frustrate the legislation.
<P2>Reasons, para. 55 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 48)</P2></P1>
<P1>e. The Q-Yes plan abused the legislative provisions related to the allocation of taxable income between provinces. The allocation formula is not intended to enable a taxpayer to avoid tax. It is intended to provide a basis for imposing tax liability in the appropriate province. Veracity obtained an establishment in Quebec for the purpose of avoiding B.C. tax when it knew it would never pay tax in Quebec. That circumvented the object and spirit of those provisions.
<P2>Reasons, para. 56 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 48)</P2></P1>
<P1>f. Veracity adopted contradictory positions about the allocation of the same income, maintaining in B.C. that 90% of its taxable income was taxable in Quebec while maintaining in Quebec that 100% of the same income was taxable in B.C. This was a clear abuse of the income allocation provisions.
<P2>Reasons, para. 56 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 48)</P2></P1>
<P1>g. The Q-Yes plan abused the legislative provisions for taxation years and fiscal year ends. Although the legislation permitted a corporation to select one fiscal period in Quebec and another for federal and B.C. tax purposes, the legislation did not contemplate a taxpayer using different fiscal periods in different jurisdictions for the same income in the same year. No legislation contemplated the Q-Yes plan's shuffle between jurisdictions.
<P2>Reasons, para. 57 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 49)</P2></P1></P>
<P>20. The trial judge distinguished this case from the case of a taxpayer selecting a &ldquo;tax haven&rdquo; country or province as a place for doing business in order to reduce tax. Veracity did not take advantage of a Quebec legislative policy intended to provide a &ldquo;tax holiday&rdquo; for Veracity's income through the Quebec provisions for fiscal periods and taxation years. The Q-Yes plan merely exploited a legislative loophole.
<P1>Reasons, para. 29 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 39)</P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ISSUES ON APPEAL</TI>
<P>21. The trial judge did not err by finding that the Q-Yes plan resulted in abusive tax avoidance. Specifically:
<P1>a. The trial judge applied the GAAR jurisprudence correctly;</P1>
<P1>b. The trial judge did not apply the B.C. GAAR to override an explicit legislative policy choice made by Quebec;</P1>
<P1>c. The trial judge did not consider provisions that are outside the scope of the BC GAAR; and</P1>
<P1>d. The trial judge correctly determined the object, spirit and purpose of the relevant statutory provisions upon which Veracity relied to obtain a tax benefit.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI>The BC GAAR framework</TI>
<P>22. The principle that taxpayers may order their affairs so as to minimize tax payable (the <EM>Duke of Westminster</EM> principle) has never been absolute. The principle is subject to various common law and legislative limits. A legislative GAAR provides a further statutory basis for denying the benefits of abusive tax planning and attempts to provide preserve certainty for taxpayers in their planning.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lipson v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2009 SCC 1</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>23. The BC GAAR lays down the conditions when tax benefits that would otherwise be available under the B.C. Act will be denied: :
<QUOTE><SEC><N>68.1</N><SSEC><N>(2)</N><SSECP>If a transaction is an avoidance transaction, the tax consequences to a person must be determined in a manner that is reasonable in the circumstances in order to deny a tax benefit that, but for this section, would result, directly or indirectly, from that transaction or from a series of transactions that includes that transaction.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1>B.C. Act, ss. 68.1(2)</P1></P>
<P>24. The key concepts in ss. 68.1(2) are &ldquo;tax benefit&rdquo;, &ldquo;avoidance transaction&rdquo;, and &ldquo;tax consequences&rdquo;. Generally, the BC GAAR will apply to deny a tax benefit when that benefit results from an avoidance transaction, and it does so by requiring that the tax position of any person be re-determined in order to deny the tax benefit.</P>
<P>25. A tax benefit is a reduction, avoidance, or deferral of tax or another amount payable, or an increase in a refund of tax or another amount, under the B.C. Act. The BC GAAR may apply whenever a transaction, or a series of transactions, results in a tax benefit.
<P1>B.C. Act, ss. 68.1(1) definition of &ldquo;tax benefit&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>26. &ldquo;Avoidance transaction&rdquo; is the central concept in the BC GAAR because a tax benefit will be denied only when it results from an avoidance transaction, or from a series of transactions that includes an avoidance transaction. A transaction is an &ldquo;avoidance transaction&rdquo; when:
<P1>a. The transaction results, directly or indirectly, in a tax benefit or is part of a series of transactions that results, directly or indirectly, in a tax benefit;</P1>
<P1>b. The transaction may not reasonably be considered to have been undertaken primarily for <EM>bona fide</EM> purposes. Obtaining a B.C. tax benefit, and avoiding tax or increasing a refund of tax under any other federal or provincial Act, are not <EM>bona fide</EM> purposes; and</P1>
<P1>c. The transaction may not reasonably be considered not to result in a misuse of a provision of the B.C. Act or in an abuse having regard to those provisions read as a whole.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The BC GAAR differs from the federal GAAR in s. 245 of the Federal Act in that it combines the misuse/abuse analysis with the meaning of avoidance transaction. Under the federal GAAR, the misuse/abuse analysis is discrete from the avoidance transaction analysis (compare ss. 245(3) and (4) of the Federal Act), such that a transaction may be an avoidance transaction but still not be subject to the GAAR.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>27. When a transaction meets those three criteria, the BC GAAR applies and the resulting tax benefit must be denied. The tax benefit is denied by determining the &ldquo;tax consequences&rdquo; to a person in a manner that is reasonable in the circumstances. Tax consequences includes a person's income, taxable income, and taxable income earned in a year in British Columbia.
<P1>B.C. Act, ss. 68.1(1) definition of &ldquo;tax consequences&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>28. In determining reasonable tax consequences in order to deny a tax benefit, the BC GAAR gives the Minister and the Court the authority make a range of adjustments notwithstanding the actual facts (such as recharacterizing the nature of payments) or the normal operation of the statute (such as by ignoring the tax effects that would otherwise result from statutory provisions).
<P1>B.C. Act, ss. 68.1(3)</P1></P>
<P>29. In its federal GAAR jurisprudence, the Supreme Court of Canada has condensed the GAAR analysis into the following three steps, which should apply equally to the BC GAAR:
<P1>a. Was there a tax benefit?</P1>
<P1>b. Was the transaction giving rise to the tax benefit an avoidance transaction?</P1>
<P1>c. Was the avoidance transaction giving rise to the tax benefit abusive?
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Canada Trustco Mortgage Co. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2005 SCC 54</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Canada Trustco</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 17</P2>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Copthorne Holdings Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 63</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Copthorne Holdings</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 33</P2></P1></P>
<P>30. The trial judge found that Veracity enjoyed a tax benefit and that the tax benefit resulted from at least four avoidance transactions that were part of the Q-Yes plan. On this appeal, the only issue is whether the Q-Yes plan results in an abuse.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The applicable standard of review</TI>
<P>31. Determining whether an avoidance transaction results in an abuse is a two-part inquiry. The first step is to determine the object, spirit, and purpose of the legislative provisions that are relied on for the tax benefit. This interpretive exercise is to be conducted using a textual, contextual, and purposive approach. The second step is to determine whether, in the factual context of the case, the avoidance transactions defeated or frustrated the object, spirit, and purpose of the provisions.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER> at paras. 44 and 55</P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Copthorne Holdings</EM></UNDER> at paras. 69&ndash;71</P1></P>
<P>32. The overall inquiry involves a mixed question of fact and law. The textual, contextual, and purposive interpretation of specific provisions of the taxing statute is essentially a question of law, but the application of those provisions to the facts of a case is necessarily fact-intensive, and whether an abuse results is a question of fact.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER> at paras. 44 and 46</P1></P>
<P>33. A trial judge's interpretation of the relevant statutory provisions relied on by a taxpayer to claim a tax benefit is reviewable on a correctness standard. By contrast, if the judge has properly interpreted the relevant statutory provisions, his determination of abuse should not be overturned absent a palpable and overriding error.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER> at para. 46</P1></P>
<P>34. In this case, the trial judge correctly followed the two-step approach outlined by the Supreme Court of Canada. His reasons disclose that he identified the object, spirit, and purpose of the relevant legislative provisions giving rise to the tax benefit, and he based his determination of abuse on whether that tax benefit was within or outside that object, spirit and purpose. There is no reason for this Court to interfere.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The trial judge appreciated the hallmarks of abusive tax avoidance</TI>
<P>35. The trial judge appreciated the hallmarks of abusive tax avoidance. He followed the principles laid down by the Supreme Court of Canada and determined that the indicators of abuse are present. He did not misdirect himself.</P>
<P>36. The trial judge recognized, as laid out in the Supreme Court of Canada's GAAR jurisprudence, that not all tax planning (and therefore not every tax benefit) is abusive. The purpose of the GAAR is to draw a line between legitimate tax reduction and abusive tax avoidance.
<P1>Reasons, para. 2 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 31)</P1></P>
<P>37. The Supreme Court of Canada has held that abusive tax avoidance will usually result in three scenarios:
<P1>a. When a taxpayer relies on specific statutory provisions in order to achieve an outcome that those provisions seek to prevent;</P1>
<P1>b. When a transaction defeats the underlying rationale of the provisions that are relied on; and</P1>
<P1>c. When the transaction circumvents the application of certain provisions in a manner that frustrates or defeats the object, spirit, or purpose of the provisions.
<P2><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER> at para. 45</P2>
<P2><UNDER><EM>Copthorne Holdings</EM></UNDER> at para. 72</P2></P1></P>
<P>38. Vacuous and artificial transactions are more likely to be abusive than substantive transactions with a basis in commercial reality. The vacuous and artificial nature of transactions may confirm their abusive nature.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mathew v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2005 SCC 55</CITE><PARANUM>62</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Canada v. Global Equity Fund Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2012 FCA 272</CITE><PARANUM>67</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>39. The inquiry asks not whether an avoidance transaction, standing alone, complies with the legislation. It focuses on the <UNDER>overall result</UNDER> of the avoidance transaction. The question is whether the tax benefit resulting from the avoidance transaction is intended by the legislation: whether it accords with the object, spirit, and purpose of the legislation, or defeats and frustrates the legislative scheme.</P>
<P>40. When an avoidance transaction forms part of a series of transactions, the abuse analysis is not narrowly focused on the avoidance transaction itself but should consider the transaction in the context of the series as a whole. A transaction that is not abusive when viewed in isolation may yet be abusive when it forms part of a series that leads to a tax benefit that is not within the object and spirit of the legislative provisions. Whether a particular transaction results in an abuse should be considered in the context of the series and its overall result.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Copthorne Holdings</EM></UNDER> at para. 72</P1>
<P1><UNDER><EM>Lipson</EM></UNDER> at para. 40</P1></P>
<P>41. The considerations mentioned in <EM>Canada Trustco</EM> and <EM>Copthorne Holdings</EM> are not independent of one another and may overlap. The overarching question is whether a tax benefit frustrates or defeats the object, spirit, or purpose of the provisions that confer it. Abuse is generally not established where it is reasonable to conclude that an avoidance transaction was within the object, spirit, or purpose of the provisions.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER> at paras. 45 and 49</P1></P>
<P>42. A GAAR is often referred to as a provision &ldquo;of last resort&rdquo;. It applies when a transaction otherwise complies with the text of the relevant provisions. Its purpose is to ensure that tax benefits accord with the object and spirit, not just the text, of those provisions. A GAAR is not, however, an exceptional provision and the Supreme Court of Canada has not described it as such. Rather, the Supreme Court held that a GAAR should be given its proper effect as a statutory provision like any other.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER> at paras. 13 and 51</P1></P>
<P>43. Although the GAAR should not be interpreted as imposing the responsibility for formulating tax policy on the courts, it does require the courts to ensure that tax benefits enjoyed by taxpayers accord with the object, spirit, and purpose of the legislation. Where taxpayers obtain benefits that are anomalous having regard to the object, spirit, and purpose of the legislation, the GAAR will deny them.</P>
<P>44. Even if a tax benefit results from a &ldquo;loophole&rdquo; in the legislation, the GAAR will deny that benefit if the benefit is anomalous having regard to the object, spirit, and purpose of the legislation. Denying that tax benefit does not amount to filling a legislative gap or loophole. Instead, it is an exercise in protecting the object, spirit, and purpose of the legislation from manipulation and abuse.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Water's Edge Village Estates (Phase II) Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2002 FCA 291</CITE><PARANUM>44&ndash;47 and 51</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The trial judge examined the correct provisions</TI>
<P>45. The trial judge correctly concluded that the relevant statutory provisions include both the provisions of the B.C. Act that establish the basis of Veracity's liability to B.C. tax, and those provisions of the Federal Act and Regulations incorporated into, or adopted by, the B.C. Act for computing tax liability. The relevant federal provisions include those for computing taxable capital gains, income, and taxable income, as well as those dealing with taxation years and fiscal periods.</P>
<P>46. Subsection 2(2) of the B.C. Act bases liability for corporate income tax on the presence of a &ldquo;permanent establishment&rdquo; in B.C. in a year. The tax payable itself is based on a corporation's &ldquo;taxable income earned in the year in British Columbia&rdquo;. &ldquo;Taxable income earned in the year in British Columbia&rdquo; is defined in s. 13.3 of the B.C. Act as the taxable income earned in the year in British Columbia as determined &ldquo;in accordance with&rdquo; regulations made under subsection 124(4) of the Federal Act.
<P1>B.C. Act, ss. 2(2), 13.3 and 14</P1></P>
<P>47. Subsection 124(4) of the Federal Act and Part IV of the Federal Regulations are the provisions that address computing a corporation's taxable income earned in a year in a particular province. Subsection 124(4) of the Federal Act provides that federal tax otherwise payable in respect of a corporation's taxable income is reduced by 10% of the amount of that income that was earned in a province. The 10% reduction provides provinces with taxing room for provincial corporate income tax.
<P1>Federal Act, ss. 124(4)</P1></P>
<P>48. Part IV of the Federal Regulations addresses computing a corporation's taxable income earned in a year in a province. The key to the computation is the presence of a permanent establishment in one or more provinces. Taxable income is allocated only to provinces in which a corporation has a permanent establishment in a year. When a corporation has a permanent establishment in multiple provinces, then its taxable income is allocated to those particular provinces using the ratio-based formula in Regulation 400.
<P1>Federal Regulations, Part IV</P1></P>
<P>49. The allocation formula in Part IV of the Federal Regulations applies to a corporation's &ldquo;taxable income&rdquo;. Subsection 2(2) of the Federal Act defines taxable income as a taxpayer's income for the year plus and minus certain additions and deductions. Section 3 of the Federal Act defines a taxpayer's income as including taxable capital gains. Taxable capital gains are computed under subdivision c of Division B of Part I of the Federal Act, primarily under ss. 38, 39 and 40. Section 85 of the Federal Act is relevant in the computation of taxable capital gains because it affects the tax values used in that computation.
<P1>Federal Act, ss. 2(2), 3, 38, 39, 40 and 85</P1></P>
<P>50. The B.C. Act provides that taxable income earned in a year in B.C. is to be determined &ldquo;in accordance with&rdquo; the Federal Regulations.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Similarly, subsection 1(1) of the B.C. Act defines &ldquo;taxable income&rdquo; as having the &ldquo;same meaning&rdquo; as in the Federal Act. For B.C. tax purposes, therefore, taxable income must be calculated using the relevant provisions of the Federal Act. This statutory scheme is how B.C.'s provincial tax base is harmonized with the Federal Act.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The result is that the federal provisions that are relevant to that determination are effectively adopted into the B.C. Act. The B.C. Act does not merely transpose amounts previously computed under federal legislation; it requires a separate determination of those amounts for B.C. tax purposes, which is carried out under the federal provisions. Accordingly, it is possible to misuse or abuse those federal provisions for B.C. purposes.
<P1>B.C. Act, ss. 1(1) definition of &ldquo;taxable income earned in a year in British Columbia&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>51. If the B.C. Act were not read as incorporating or adopting those federal provisions, the BC GAAR would be deprived of meaning. It would not apply to transactions that directly result in the avoidance of B.C. tax through the manipulation or abuse of federal provisions that are necessary to compute income and taxable income. There would be no statutory mechanism to protect the integrity of the B.C. tax base. The BC GAAR would effectively be read out of the B.C. Act.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The federal GAAR could not be used to prevent abuses of federal provisions that result in provincial tax avoidance because it does not recognize the avoidance of provincial tax as a tax benefit or a non-<EM>bona fide</EM> purpose.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>52. The Tax Collection Agreement between Canada and B.C. does not prevent applying the BC GAAR to protect the provincial tax base, particularly when the provincial tax base is not identical to the federal tax base because only the portion of taxable income allocated to B.C. is taxable provincially.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gendis Inc. v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2006 MBCA 58</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The trial judge correctly identified the object, spirit, and purpose of the relevant provisions and found an abuse</TI>
<P>53. It is evident from the trial judge's reasons that he did identify the object, spirit, and purpose of the relevant statutory provisions. He referred to their object, spirit, and purpose throughout his reasons and based his findings that the Q-Yes plan resulted in an abuse of the B.C. Act on that understanding. Not only did he find it reasonable to conclude that the Q-Yes plan resulted in abusive tax avoidance, but he found the abuse to be clear. His findings are correct and should not be disturbed.</P>
<P>54. The overall result of the Q-Yes plan is that a B.C. corporation avoided B.C. tax on a substantial capital gain simply by purchasing units of a publicly traded limited partnership carrying on business in Quebec. The trial judge found this result to abuse a range of legislative provisions.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Q-Yes plan resulted in an abuse of s. 85</UNDER></TI>
<P>55. The trial judge correctly recognized that, although the <UNDER>effect</UNDER> of s. 85 is to permit a taxpayer to dispose of property without realizing a taxable capital gain on the disposition, the object and spirit of the provision extends to deferring and preserving the tax associated with such a transfer. In light of that object and spirit, the Q-Yes plan resulted in an abuse.</P>
<P>56. The trial judge's conclusion reflects that s. 85 functions not only to defer tax that would be payable on a disposition, but to preserve that tax in the hands of both the transferring taxpayer (by fixing the transferor's tax cost of the shares received as consideration for the property) and the receiving corporation (by fixing the corporation's tax cost of the transferred property). It has long been recognized that s. 85 actually creates the potential for double taxation in relation to the deferred gain, and that this consequence is intended.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Continental Bank of Canada v. Canada</SOC><YEAR>1994</YEAR><CITE>94 D.T.C. 1858</CITE><COURTJUR>T.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 107</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ceco Operations Ltd. v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2006 TCC 256</CITE><PARANUM>72&ndash;74</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>57. Rollover provisions like s. 85 permit taxpayers to reorganize the manner in which they hold assets without incurring immediate tax consequences when their underlying economic interest is unchanged. Part of a rollover provision's purpose, therefore, is necessarily to preserve the deferred tax to ensure that it is ultimately paid when the property is disposed of to an arm's length party.
<P1>Stanley E. Edwards, &ldquo;Statutory amalgamations and recapitalizations&rdquo;, 1972 Conference Report (Toronto: Canadian Tax Foundation, 1973) 401</P1></P>
<P>58. The trial judge's finding that the Q-Yes plan results in an abuse of s. 85 recognizes that <UNDER>using</UNDER> a provision for a purpose for which it is not intended is an indicator of abuse. The trial judge recognized that s. 85 is ultimately a tax deferring, not a tax relieving, provision. Section 85 is not intended to permit tax to be avoided completely. Yet, in this case, s. 85 was used to avoid the tax completely by putting the ALI shares and the associated gain in the hands of a different taxpayer who could avoid tax completely on 90% of that gain. The trial judge found that using a tax deferral provision in this manner abuses the object and spirit of the provision. His finding echoes statements in other cases considering rollover provisions, and should not be disturbed.
<P1><UNDER><EM>Mathew</EM></UNDER> at para. 58</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>OGT Holdings Ltd. v. Quebec</SOC><CITE>2006 Q.C.C.Q. 6328</CITE><COURTJUR>C.Q.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 200; affirmed <UNDER>2009 Q.C.C.A. 191</UNDER> at pars. 21&ndash;35; leave to appeal refused <UNDER>[2009] S.C.C.A. 136</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Antle v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2009 TCC 465</CITE><PARANUM>91</PARANUM></CASEREF>, affirmed on other grounds <UNDER>2010 FCA 280</UNDER></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Q-Yes plan resulted in an abuse of the provisions dealing with capital gains</UNDER></TI>
<P>59. The trial judge found the Q-Yes plan to result in an abuse of the provisions of the Federal Act dealing with the computation of income, taxable income, and taxable income earned in British Columbia because the plan permitted a realized capital gain to be included in income but not taxed. The relevant statutory provisions include ss. 3, 38, 39 and 40 of the Federal Act, which provide for the computation of taxable capital gains which are included in taxable income.</P>
<P>60. The Q-Yes plan resulted in capital gains being realized and briefly included in income but then allocated out of the taxable income actually subject to tax. Such transactions frustrate the purpose of the applicable provisions. Although the effect of ss. 3, 38, 39, and 40 is to compute taxable capital gains and include them in income, and does not extend to subjecting those gains to tax, the object and spirit of those provisions is broader. The obvious purpose of those provisions is to subject realized gains on capital to taxation on the same basis as ordinary income, as increases to a taxpayer's economic power. The trial judge found the Q-Yes plan to frustrate that purpose&mdash;a hallmark of abuse.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Triad Gestco Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2012 FCA 258</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Q-Yes Plan resulted in an abuse of the provincial income allocation provisions</UNDER></TI>
<P>61. The trial judge correctly found that the Q-Yes plan resulted in an abuse of the provincial income allocation provisions in the Federal Act and Regulations. The judge recognized that the allocation formula based on the presence of a permanent establishment is intended to provide a basis for imposing tax liability in the appropriate province. A permanent establishment is the foundation of a corporation's liability to provincial income tax. It is not intended to provide an avenue for avoiding provincial tax.
<P1>Reasons, para. 56 (Appeal Record, Tab 4, p. 48)</P1></P>
<P>62. The trial judge correctly held that by acquiring a permanent establishment in Quebec for the purpose of avoiding B.C. tax when it knew that it would not in fact be liable to Quebec tax, Veracity circumvented the object and spirit of the income allocation provisions and used them for a purpose for which they were not intended.</P>
<P>63. The trial judge also recognized that the object and spirit of the income allocation rules is to ensure that income is neither over-taxed nor under-taxed. It is not limited to preventing taxation of the same income by more than one province. As outlined by Ernest Smith, the purpose of a provincial income allocation formula is to determine the amount of a corporation's taxable income that can rightly be regarded as having been earned in a particular taxing jurisdiction. That determination serves the dual purpose of preventing over-taxation and under-taxation:
<QUOTE><P>...to the extent that different jurisdictions have different answers to the question, &ldquo;What profit should be attributed to the business activities carried on in each jurisdiction?&rdquo;, more or less than 100% of the corporation's profits may be taxed. Unless an appropriate answer to this question is found, the same corporate profits may be taxed at the same time by two or more taxing jurisdictions (double or multiple taxation), or profits that cannot rightly be regarded as having been earned in a particular jurisdiction may be taxed by that jurisdiction (over-taxation, or excessive taxation), or <UNDER>profits that should be taxable in one jurisdiction or another may become incapable of being taxed in any (under-taxation)</UNDER>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Ernest Smith, &ldquo;Allocating to Provinces the Taxable Income of Corporations: How the Federal-Provincial Allocation Rules Evolved&rdquo;, (1976) vol. 24, no. 5 Can Tax. J. 545&ndash;571 at 545</P1></P>
<P>64. The object, spirit, and purpose of a corporate income allocation formula, therefore, is not simply to allocate income to provinces, but to ensure that 100%, not more and not less, of a corporation's taxable income that should be taxed in provinces in which the corporation has a permanent establishment, is allocated to those provinces.</P>
<P>65. Further, the income allocation provisions are intended to ensure that each province receives a fair allocation of revenue. The drafters of the provincial income allocation rules were concerned with legality, acceptability, and fairness both to taxpayers and to provincial treasuries. The purpose is not to provide avenues to avoid tax in a particular province, or to avoid taxation in any province at all.
<P1>Smith at p. 567</P1></P>
<P>66. Accordingly, it is not the absence of tax liability in Quebec that results in an abuse of the income allocation provisions for B.C. purposes; it is the acquisition of a permanent establishment in Quebec and the manipulation of the components of the income allocation formula for the primary purpose of avoiding B.C. tax that results in an abuse of the B.C. provisions.</P>
<P>67. The trial judge further held that, pursuant to the Q-Yes plan, Veracity made contradictory representations to each province about the same income. It filed in Quebec on the basis that 100% of its taxable income in the year ending August 31, 2002 (including the Taxable Gain) was allocable to B.C., while it filed in B.C. on the basis that 90% of that same income (including the Taxable Gain) was allocable to Quebec, not to B.C. The trial judge was correct to describe these as contradictory positions, and he found them to be a clear abuse of the provincial income allocation provisions.</P>
<P>68. In agreeing to harmonize its tax statute with the Federal Act, the B.C. legislature cannot reasonably be taken to have intended that income that would have been taxable in B.C. may be allocated to another province for B.C. tax purposes while in that other province the very same income is allocated to B.C. This is particularly so when the income allocation is the result of avoidance transactions manufactured for the primary purpose of avoiding B.C. tax, and with the knowledge that tax will not be paid in the other province. At that point, the allocation becomes a pretext.</P>
<P>69. The trial judge did not base his finding of abuse on an erroneous assumption that there is a uniform system of provincial taxation in Canada. The trial judge based his finding of abuse on the use that Veracity made of the provincial income allocation provisions under the B.C. Act in order to permanently avoid B.C. tax.</P>
<P>70. In any event, the system of provincial taxation in Canada is more uniform than the appellant argues. There is generally a uniform tax base among the provinces. The relevant inter-provincial difference in this case relates to Quebec's decision to administer and collect its provincial income tax independently, not to different taxation policies in Quebec that do not tax Veracity's income.</P>
<P>71. Although Quebec is not an agreeing province, it has effectively harmonized its tax base with the federal tax base, and its formula for allocating corporate taxable income to Quebec is materially identical to the formula in the Federal Regulations used by the agreeing provinces. Quebec made no policy choice to exempt Veracity's income or to provide a tax holiday for income like Veracity's. Quebec is not the provincial tax haven of Canada.
<P1>Report of the Technical Committee on Business Taxation (Department of Finance Canada, 1997) p. 11.2</P1>
<P1>Smith, <EM>supra</EM> at p. 564 and 565</P1>
<P1>Quebec Act, ss. 27 and 771(2)</P1>
<P1><EM>Regulation respecting the Taxation Act</EM>, C.L.Q.R. c. I-3, r. 1, s. 771R4</P1>
<P1>Reasons, para. 29 (Appeal Record Tab 4, p. 39)</P1></P>
<P>72. The different treatment in Quebec resulted from Quebec's decision to administer its income tax system independently of the federal government and the agreeing provinces. That decision permitted Veracity to select a different taxation year in Quebec than its taxation year for federal and B.C. purposes. Quebec's decision to administer its income tax system separately does not, however, represent a legislative policy of providing avenues for taxpayers in other provinces to avoid tax in their home provinces.
<P1>Finances Quebec, &ldquo;Minister's Statement Concerning a Reduction in Payroll Taxes to Create Jobs and Other Tax Measures&rdquo;, Bulletin d'information 96-9, December 19, 1996, p. 10</P1>
<P1>Finances Quebec, &ldquo;1998-1999 Budget Additional Information on the Budgetary Measures&rdquo;, p. 73</P1>
<P1>Finances Quebec, &ldquo;Adjustments to Various Measures and Harmonization with Federal Legislation&rdquo;, Information Bulletin 2006 6, December 20, 2006, p. 10</P1>
<P1>Finances Quebec, &ldquo;2008-2009 Budget Additional Information on the Budgetary Measures&rdquo;, March 13, 2008, pp. A.116-A.117</P1></P>
<P>73. Further, the trial judge correctly declined to follow the &ldquo;inter-jurisdictional&rdquo; tax avoidance cases relied on by the appellant (<EM>Husky Energy, Canada Safeway, Inter-Leasing</EM> and <EM>MIL Investments</EM>). Those cases are all distinguishable because they dealt with taxpayers arranging their affairs to take advantage of deliberate policy choices by another jurisdiction either to exempt particular income flows from taxation (such as non-taxation in Ontario of interest income earned by a non-resident corporation with an establishment in Ontario), or to provide tax incentives as a tax haven-like jurisdiction (Luxembourg's decision to provide a &ldquo;participation exemption&rdquo; for shareholdings by a Luxembourg company in a foreign company). In this case, the trial judge recognized that Quebec made no such policy choice and he clearly distinguished those cases.</P>
<P>74. The trial judge recognized that this case is more like <EM>OGT Holdings</EM>, in which the Quebec Court of Appeal upheld the application of the Quebec GAAR to prevent tax avoidance resulting from desynchronized federal and Quebec elections. In <EM>OGT Holdings</EM>, as in this case, Ontario did not have a policy of not taxing the capital gain that the taxpayer had deferred in Quebec. Instead, that capital gain never entered the Ontario provincial tax base because of the disconnect between the Quebec and federal s. 85 elections.</P>
<P>75. The Quebec Court of Appeal held that the OGT tax plan &ldquo;twisted&rdquo; and &ldquo;distorted&rdquo; the Quebec provisions by obtaining a deferral that presupposed that the gain would be taxable On a subsequent disposition when the taxpayer knew that the gain would not in fact be taxable and would simply evaporate from the tax base. Accordingly, the tax plan obtained tax deferral treatment on the basis of a &ldquo;pretext&rdquo;.
<P1><UNDER><EM>OGT Holdings Ltd.</EM> (Q.C.A.)</UNDER> at paras. 21&ndash;34</P1></P>
<P>76. The trial judge recognized the similarities between the OGT tax plan and the Q-Yes plan. Veracity allocated $8.7 million of taxable income to Quebec for B.C. purposes with the knowledge that it would allocate all of that same income back to B.C. for Quebec purposes and the income would never be subject to Quebec tax.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Q-Yes plan resulted in an abuse of the &ldquo;fiscal period&rdquo; and &ldquo;taxation year&rdquo; provisions</UNDER></TI>
<P>77. The trial judge correctly held that the Q-Yes plan results in an abuse of the &ldquo;fiscal period&rdquo; provisions in the B.C. Act. The abuse does not result from Veracity's selection of a Quebec fiscal period, but from the selection of a B.C. fiscal period as part of a plan to avoid B.C. tax.</P>
<P>78. The legislative provisions respecting fiscal periods and taxation years permit a corporation to select the period for which tax is computed and reported annually. The statutory scheme requires a corporation to select a fiscal period, which becomes the corporation's taxation year. Under the B.C. Act, &ldquo;taxation year&rdquo; and &ldquo;fiscal period&rdquo; have the same meaning as in the Federal Act. The Federal Act defines fiscal period as the period for which the accounts of a business are made up for purposes of assessment under the Act. The only limit on the selection of a fiscal period under the Federal Act is that the period may not exceed 53 weeks.
<P1>B.C. Act, s. 1 definitions of &ldquo;fiscal period&rdquo; and &ldquo;taxation year&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>Federal Act, ss. 249(1) and 249.1(1)</P1></P>
<P>79. The object and spirit of the fiscal period provisions is clear: to facilitate the regular and periodic reporting of tax results. The choice of fiscal period can be influenced by numerous factors, including business, financial and tax reporting purposes. There would not normally be a commercial justification for selecting different fiscal periods in different jurisdictions for the same income in the same year. The flexibility accorded by the legislative scheme does not extend to providing a means to time fiscal periods so as to render provincial tax optional.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Fredette v. The Queen</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>55 D.T.C. 621</CITE><COURTJUR>T.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 64&ndash;68</P1>
<P1>IC 88-2, <EM>General Anti Avoidance Rule</EM>, October 21, 1988, para. 2</P1></P>
<P>80. The trial judge found that the primary purpose in selecting a June 30 B.C. fiscal period was to avoid B.C. tax through the Q-Yes plan. That purpose was achieved by selecting a fiscal period that allowed the Taxable Gain to be reported in B.C. after an allocation of revenues and salaries by Gaz Metro had occurred.</P>
<P>81. The purpose in selecting an August 31 fiscal period end in Quebec was clearly to ensure that the Taxable Gain was reported after the Gaz Metro acquisition but before any revenue/salary allocation by Gaz. That timing ensured that no tax would be payable in Quebec.</P>
<P>82. The trial judge's comment that the entire plan &ldquo;pivoted&rdquo; on the anomalous provision in Quebec recognizes that the Q-Yes plan would have held no attraction to Veracity if it had to pay Quebec tax. However, the choice of Quebec fiscal period did not contribute to the avoidance of B.C. tax. Veracity avoided B.C. tax through selecting a B.C. fiscal period that enabled it to purchase Gaz Metro units and to receive an allocation of revenues and salaries before reporting the Taxable Gain in B.C.</P>
<P>83. Accordingly, the trial judge did not apply the BC GAAR to Veracity's use of a Quebec legislative provision and did not override a legislative policy choice of Quebec. Denying the tax benefit realized in B.C. is unrelated to whether or not Veracity is entitled to select the Quebec fiscal period of its choosing.</P>
<P>84. Further, although the primary purpose for selecting the Quebec fiscal period was to avoid Quebec tax, that transaction was an integral part of the Q-Yes plan and is a relevant consideration under the BC GAAR. An avoidance transaction includes a transaction undertaken primarily to avoid tax under any other federal or provincial Act, including Quebec, and where that transaction results in an abuse of the B.C. Act the BC GAAR will apply.
<P1>B.C. Act, ss. 68.1(1) definition of &ldquo;avoidance transaction&rdquo; para. (c)(ii)</P1></P>
<P>85. The trial judge recognized that the flexibility permitted in the choice of fiscal period for federal and B.C. tax purposes is not intended to facilitate tax avoidance. The Q-Yes plan twisted and distorted the fiscal period principles by using that flexibility to avoid tax completely, which is not contemplated by those provisions.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>86. The respondent seeks an Order dismissing the appeal with costs.</P>
<P>87. All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>Dated at the City of Vancouver, in the Province of British Columbia, this May 31<SUP>st</SUP> of 2016.</P>
