<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Crown's basic errors</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The Crown's argument in this Court is based on the same incorrect premise as the decision under appeal&mdash;that provincial tax &ldquo;ought to have been paid somewhere&rdquo; (see &para;19&ndash;21 of Veracity's factum).</P>
<P>2. The GAAR is an exceptional provision and the Crown errs in stating the contrary in &para;42 of its factum; see <CASEREF><SOC>Copthorne Holdings Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 63</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2011] 3 S.C.R. 721</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, &para;66. <CASEREF><SOC>Canada Trustco Mortgage Co. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[2005] 2 S.C.R. 601</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF>). Under the GAAR, Parliament has conferred on the court the unusual duty of going behind the words of legislation to determine the object, spirit or purpose of the provisions relied upon by the taxpayer. The court may override the treatment afforded by those provisions but only if the Crown can identify an unambiguous policy that underlies the relevant provisions and demonstrate clear abuse. The standard is high.</P>
<P>3. Because of the GAAR's exceptional nature, the Supreme Court of Canada has confirmed on several occasions the analytical discipline that must be followed in considering the GAAR. This ensures that the GAAR does not become a standardless sweep.</P>
<P>4. An uninformed subjective impression as to what ought to be taxed, or what the tax consequences of a transaction ought to be, has no place in a GAAR analysis. That is especially so at the stage where it is necessary to determine, as a matter of law, the object and purpose of any taxing provision that is alleged to have been abused or misused.</P>
<P>5. The Crown's factum is replete with rhetoric about provincial tax avoidance but skips over the rigour required to demonstrate abuse based on the text, context and purpose of the provisions of the BC Act relied on by Veracity. The Crown does not come close to discharging the heavy burden of proving that the BC GAAR applies.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The provincial tax scheme</UNDER></TI>
<P>6. The Crown's incorrect premise reflects a misunderstanding of the scheme of provincial taxation. Contrary to &para;61&ndash;66 of the Crown's factum, the provinces have NOT created a comprehensive provincial tax net that catches or is intended to catch all income (see the Veracity factum, paragraphs &para;42&ndash;46 and &para;66&ndash;83).</P>
<P>7. And contrary to &para;63&ndash;65 of the Crown's factum, the purpose of the provincial allocation rules is not to prevent under-taxation. The Smith article cited by the Crown does not support the Crown's argument. Smith observes that only if there is perfect harmonization among jurisdictions will 100% of a corporation's profits (not more not less) be taxed. Both double taxation and non-taxation could be avoided if all provinces had identical allocation rules and measured taxable income at the same time.</P>
<P>8. That hypothetical harmonized system does not exist. Quebec's taxation year rule permitted taxpayers to measure income at different times. When that variable is different for different provinces, income can be double-taxed or not taxed at all. In the context of tax law, timing is everything (see Arnold et al in <EM>&ldquo;Timing and Income Taxation&rdquo;</EM> at p. 3).</P>
<P>9. Quebec chose not to harmonize its taxation year rules with those of the other provinces. The obvious and well understood consequence of that choice is that some income of a taxpayer who is taxable in Quebec and another province might fall between provincial tax nets. However, that cannot possibly mean, as the Crown suggests in &para;66 of its factum, that it is an abuse of the BC Act for a BC taxpayer to become at the same time a Quebec taxpayer by acquiring a permanent establishment in Quebec.</P>
<P>10. Contrary to &para;70&ndash;73 of the Crown's factum, Quebec's permissive rule for choosing a taxation year is not simply part of Quebec's decision to administer its income tax system independently. Both the determination of the type of income that will be taxed and when it will be measured affect the income that will be taxed by a province. Quebec's unique rule permitting a different taxation year is one of hundreds of provisions in the Quebec Act that reflect deliberate tax policy choices made by the Quebec legislature, upon which all Quebec taxpayers are entitled to rely. The Crown cannot rely on the BC GAAR to remedy its grievance that because Veracity became liable to Quebec tax, BC was allocated only 10.2% of Veracity's capital gain.
<P1>See Leah Plumridge and Daniel Sandler &ldquo;Quebec &lsquo;Year-End Shuffle&rsquo; Subject to Provincial GAAR&rdquo;, Canadian Tax Journal Vol. 64, No 2 (2016) (publication pending)</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The trial judge did not &ldquo;clearly distinguish&rdquo; guiding appellate authority</UNDER></TI>
<P>11. Veracity says (see &para;47&ndash;51 of the Veracity factum) that the appellate court decisions in <UNDER><EM>Husky Energy</EM></UNDER>, <UNDER><EM>Canada Safeway</EM></UNDER>, <UNDER><EM>Inter-Leasing</EM></UNDER> and <UNDER><EM>MIL Investments</EM></UNDER> are central to this case. These cases support the conclusion that it was not an abuse of the BC Act for Veracity to take advantage of Quebec's taxation year rule. The Crown's response (&para;73 of the Crown's factum) is that the judge &ldquo;clearly distinguished&rdquo; these cases. The judge does not mention any of these cases in his reasons for judgment. He did not even address these cases, let alone &ldquo;clearly distinguish&rdquo; them.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Crown has not met its burden of establishing a clear abuse of the BC Act</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. The Crown states incorrectly, at &para;80 of its factum, that the trial judge found that the primary purpose in selecting a June 30 BC year end was to avoid BC tax. The trial judge held that the selection of different fiscal periods was an avoidance transaction and that the entire plan pivoted on the anomalous Quebec provision.</P>
<P>13. Although the Crown identifies, at &para;77&ndash;85 of its factum, the object and purpose of certain provisions of the BC Act (specifically, the provisions dealing with &ldquo;fiscal period&rdquo; and &ldquo;taxation year&rdquo;), and states that Veracity made use of them to avoid tax (which is admitted), the Crown has failed to specify how those provisions were abused, except to assert that they were not intended to facilitate tax avoidance.</P>
<P>14. That falls far short of the substantial burden on the Crown to establish clear abuse of a provision of the BC Act. In determining misuse or abuse, it is not enough to assert that the provisions relied upon by the taxpayer are not intended to provide a means of avoiding tax. If that were enough, the GAAR would apply in every case, and the misuse or abuse test would be meaningless; see <CASEREF><SOC>Inter-Leasing, Inc. v. Ontario (Revenue)</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 575</CITE><PARANUM>66</PARANUM></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>The approach taken by the appeal judge&mdash;to define the purpose of the provision as to raise revenue and to define the tax base as broadly as possible&mdash;renders &ldquo;abusive&rdquo; any transaction that has the effect of reducing tax. I do not accept this approach.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>15. Nor is it enough to assert, as the Crown does in &para;68 of its factum, that the legislature did not foresee a particular result. It is well established that the GAAR cannot be used to fill gaps in legislation, even if the transaction was not foreseen by the legislature (see the Veracity factum at &para;33). In any event, the gap at issue in this case is in the Quebec Act and the Quebec legislature responded.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Crown's reliance on provisions of the federal Act</UNDER></TI>
<P>16. With respect to paragraphs &para;45, &para;49&ndash;51, and &para;55&ndash;60 of the Crown's factum, Veracity does not dispute that the BC GAAR may apply to the abuse of a provision that is incorporated by reference into the BC Act. However, such incorporation by reference must be expressly stated in the BC Act.</P>
<P>17. Contrary to the Crown's argument, none of the provisions of the federal Act that the judge found to have been abused (ss. 3, 38, 39, 40 and 85) are incorporated by reference into the BC Act. It is imprecise and inaccurate to say they are &ldquo;effectively adopted&rdquo; into the BC Act. Therefore, it was not open to the judge to find that the BC GAAR applied to what he concluded was an abuse of any of those provisions (see paragraphs &para;37&ndash;41 and &para;84&ndash;86 of Veracity's factum).</P>
<P>18. Veracity's interpretation of the BC GAAR does not deprive the BC GAAR of meaning, as the Crown argues in &para;51 of its factum. The BC GAAR applies to tax avoidance transactions that abuse any provision of the BC Act, such as the numerous tax credits that BC provides to meet provincial policy objectives and other specific provisions specific to BC. But the BC GAAR has a limited scope. The legislature of BC enacted a BC GAAR which does not extend to misuses or abuses of provisions of the federal Act, in sharp contrast to the Ontario GAAR. The plain text of the BC GAAR is consistent with BC's status as an agreeing province, and its agreement to use the federal taxable base. It is not for this Court to legislate a change to the BC GAAR.</P>
<P>19. In any event, the provisions of the federal Act cited by the Crown were not abused. See &para;85&ndash;88 of Veracity's factum.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Responses to specific points made by the Crown</UNDER></TI>
<P>20. The Crown cites at &para;38 of its factum two cases in which the courts found certain transactions to be abusive and commented that this conclusion was confirmed by their &ldquo;vacuous or artificial&rdquo; nature. To be clear, the judge did not find that the transactions in this case were vacuous or artificial.</P>
<P>21. In <UNDER><EM>Canada Trustco</EM></UNDER>, the Crown made similar allegations, as it does in many GAAR cases, about the transactions at issue (see &para;57&ndash;60). The Supreme Court of Canada was not distracted by the rhetoric and found that the Crown had failed to meet the high standard for demonstrating abuse. The GAAR did not apply.</P>
<P>22. All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>Dated at the City of Vancouver, Province of British Columbia, this June 7<SUP>th</SUP> of 2016.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Monica Biringer/Al Meghji/David Ross</P>
<P>Appellant</P></BLOCK2>
